# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: early-modern-period
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The **10th millennium BC** spanned the years 10,000 BC to 9001 BC (c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] It marks the beginning of the transition from the Palaeolithic to the Neolithic via the interim Mesolithic (Northern Europe and Western Europe) and Epipaleolithic (Levant and Near East) periods, which together form the first part of the Holocene epoch that is generally believed to have begun c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 11.7 ka) and is the current geological epoch.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] It is impossible to precisely date events that happened around the time of this millennium, and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological analysis, anthropological analysis, and radiometric dating.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The main characteristic of the Holocene has been the worldwide abundance of *Homo sapiens sapiens* (humankind).
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The epoch began in the wake of the Würm glaciation, generally known as the Last Ice Age, which began 109 ka and ended 14 ka, when *Homo sapiens sapiens* was in the Palaeolithic (Old Stone) Age.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Following the Late Glacial Interstadial from 14 ka to 12.9 ka, during which global temperatures rose significantly, the Younger Dryas began.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] This was a temporary reversal of climatic warming to glacial conditions in the Northern Hemisphere and coincided with the end of the Upper Palaeolithic.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 9700 BC, marking the cutover from Pleistocene to Holocene.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] In the geologic time scale, there are three (tentatively four) stratigraphic stages of the Holocene beginning c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The starting point for the Greenlandian is the Global Boundary Stratotype Section and Point (GSSP) sample from the North Greenland Ice Core Project, which has been correlated with the Younger Dryas.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Greenlandian was succeeded by the "Northgrippian" (to c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] All three stages were officially ratified by the International Commission on Stratigraphy in July 2018.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] It has been proposed that the Meghalayan should be terminated c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 1950 and succeeded by a new stage provisionally called "Anthropocene".
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] In the Holocene's first millennium, the Palaeolithic began to be superseded by the Neolithic (New Stone) Age which lasted about 6,000 years, depending on location.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The gradual transition period is sometimes termed Mesolithic (northern and western Europe) or Epipalaeolithic (Levant and Near East).
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The glaciers retreated as the world climate became warmer and that inspired an agricultural revolution, though at first, the dog was probably the only domesticated animal.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] This was accompanied by a social revolution in that humans gained from agriculture the impetus to settle.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Settlement is the key precursor to civilisation, which cannot be achieved by a nomadic lifestyle.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 10,000 BC, is believed to have been more or less stable.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] It has been estimated that there were some five million people at the time of the Last Glacial Maximum, growing to forty million by 5000 BC and 100 million by 1600 BC, which is an average growth rate of 0.027% p.a. from the Neolithic to the Middle Bronze Age.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Around 10,000 BC, most people lived in hunter-gatherer communities scattered across all continents except Antarctica and Zealandia.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] As the Würm/Wisconsin ended, settlement of northern regions was again possible.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Agriculture developed in different parts of the world at different times.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] In many places, people learned how to cultivate without outside help; elsewhere, as in western Europe, the skills were imported.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] A decrease in human height accompanied the rise of agriculture near the start of the Holocene period (10,000 BC) and was later correlated with urban population density.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Natufian culture prevailed in the Levant through the 10th millennium and was unusual in that it supported a sedentary or semi-sedentary population even before the introduction of agriculture.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] An early example is 'Ain Mallaha, which may have been the first village in which people were wholly sedentary.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Natufian people are believed to have founded another early settlement on the site of Jericho (Tell es-Sultan) where there is evidence of building between 9600 BC and 8200 BC.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Dates for the Natufian are indeterminate and range broadly from c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] It is possible that the early cultivation of figs began in the Jordan River valley sometime after the middle of the 10th millennium.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Besides the fig trees, the people may have begun cultivation of wild plants such as barley and pistachio; and they possibly began herding goats, pigs and cattle.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Agriculture began to be developed by the various communities of the Fertile Crescent, which included the Levant, but it would not be widely practised for another 2,000 years by which time Neolithic culture was becoming well established in many parts of the Near East.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Among the earliest cultivated plants were forms of millet and rice grown in the Middle East, possibly in this millennium but more likely after 9000 BC.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] By about 9500 BC, people in south-eastern Anatolia were harvesting wild grasses and grains.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The earliest evidence of sheep herding has been found in northern Iraq, dated before 9000 BC.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Prehistoric chronology is almost entirely reliant upon the dating of material objects of which pottery is by far the most widespread and the most resistant to decay.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] All locations and generations developed their own shapes, sizes and styles of pottery, including methods and styles of decoration, but there was consistency among stratified deposits and even shards can be classified by time and place.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Pottery is believed to have been discovered independently in various places, beginning with China c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 18,000 BC, and was probably created accidentally by fires lit on clay soil.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The main discovery of pottery dated to the 10th millennium has been at Bosumpra Cave (early tenth-millennium cal.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] BC) on the Kwahu Plateau in southeastern Ghana and Ounjougou (c.9400 BC) in Central Mali, providing evidence of an independent invention of pottery in Sub-Saharan Africa in different climatic zones.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The first chronological pottery system was the Early, Middle and Late Minoan framework devised in the early 20th century by Sir Arthur Evans for his findings at Knossos.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] This covered the Bronze Age in twelve phases from c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 1050 BC and the principle was later extended to mainland Greece (Helladic) and the Aegean islands (Cycladic).
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Dame Kathleen Kenyon was the principal archaeologist at Tell es-Sultan (ancient Jericho) and she discovered that there was no pottery there.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The potter's wheel had not yet been invented and, where pottery as such was made, it was still hand-built, often by means of coiling, and pit fired.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Kenyon discovered vessels such as bowls, cups, and plates at Jericho which were made from stone.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] She reasonably surmised that others made from wood or vegetable fibres would have long since decayed.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Using Evans' system as a benchmark, Kenyon divided the Near East Neolithic into phases called Pre-Pottery Neolithic A (PPNA), from c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 8800 BC; Pre-Pottery Neolithic B (PPNB), from c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 6500 BC; and then Pottery Neolithic (PN), which had varied start-points from c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 6500 BC until the beginnings of the Bronze Age towards the end of the 4th millennium.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] In the 10th millennium, the Natufian culture co-existed with the PPNA which prevailed in the Levantine and upper Mesopotamian areas of the Fertile Crescent.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] In North Africa, Saharan rock art engravings in what is known as the Bubalus (Large Wild Fauna) period have been dated to between 10,000 BC and 7000 BC.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Wall paintings found in Ethiopia and Eritrea depict human activity; some of the older paintings are thought to date back to around 10,000 BC.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] In Prehistoric Egypt, a culture of hunter-gatherers replaced a grain grinding culture in 10,000 BC.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Abu Madi tel mounds in the Sinai Peninsula have been dated c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Clovis culture was widely distributed throughout North America.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The people were hunter-gatherers and the culture's duration is believed to have been from c.9050 BC to c.8800 BC.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] There is evidence of increasing use of Clovis point tool technology for hunting.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Elsewhere in North America, the Petroglyphs at Winnemucca Lake, in what is today northwest Nevada, were carved by this time, possibly as early as 12.8 ka or as late as 10 ka.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The sites at Göbekli Tepe, which is home to megalithic structures, Hallan Çemi Tepesi, both in south-eastern Anatolia, and at Tell Qaramel, in north-west Syria, may have been occupied during this millennium.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] It was found out that gastronomy first emerged in Göbekli Tepe in this millennium.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] This most important discovery shedding light on the beginning of gastronomy in Anatolia consists of religious places in which feasts were held in this millennium that were found in the archaeological excavations conducted in Göbekli Tepe in Urfa province which is called the zero point of time.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Sassi di Matera in southern Italy is believed to have been the site of human settlement since the Paleolithic period in this millennium, making it one of the oldest continuously inhabited settlements in history.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] At the Hasankeyf Mound in Turkey, Europe, almost all archaeological data date to this millennium.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] In Great Britain, which was not then an island, the Star Carr site in North Yorkshire is believed to have been inhabited by Maglemosian peoples for about 800 years from c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Bhimbetka rock shelters, which feature prehistoric cave paintings, earliest being dated to 10,000 BCE, corresponds to the Indian Mesolithic.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] These sites would have been home to a nomadic/hunting society existing in this region.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] In the southern hemisphere, rising sea levels had gradually formed Bass Strait, separating Tasmania from mainland Australia.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] This process is believed to have been complete by about the beginning of the 10th millennium.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Bass Strait had been a plain populated by indigenous people who are thought to have first arrived around 40,000 years ago.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Wisconsin glaciation had sheeted much of North America and, as it retreated, its meltwaters created an immense proglacial lake now known as Lake Agassiz.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Sometime after 10,000 BC, the retreating glaciers created the rock formation on Cannon Mountain in present-day New Hampshire that was known as the Old Man of the Mountain until its collapse in 2003.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The ongoing Quaternary System/Period represents the last 2.58 million years since the end of the Neogene and is officially divided into the Pleistocene and Holocene Series/Epochs.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Holocene has been assigned an age of 11,700 calendar years before 2000 CE which means it began c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] It is preceded in the geological time scale by the Late Pleistocene sub-epoch, also known as the Tarantian Stage/Age, which awaits formal ratification by the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) and tentatively spans the time from c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] Preceding the Late Pleistocene is the Middle Pleistocene sub-epoch, or Chibanian Stage/Age, which also awaits ratification and tentatively spans the time from c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] 773,000 is sub-divided into two Stages/Ages which have been officially defined: the Gelasian (until c.
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Holocene calendar, devised by Cesare Emiliani in 1993, places its epoch at 10,000 BC (with the year 2026 being rendered as 12026 HE).
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] The Human Era calendar attempts to simplify the calculation of time spans across the BC-CE divide by designating a more universally relevant epoch date: the start of human settlements (instead of the birth of Jesus Christ).
[src:early-modern-period/10-000-bce] CE dates can be converted by adding 10,000 years; converting BC dates requires subtraction from 10,001 (since the Gregorian calendar lacks a year zero).
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] The **16th century** begins with the Julian year 1501 (MDI) and ends with either the Julian or the Gregorian year 1600 (MDC) (depending on the reckoning used; the Gregorian calendar introduced a lapse of 10 days in October 1582).
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] The Habsburg Spanish Empire, Portuguese Empire, Ottoman Empire, Safavid Persia, Mughal India and Ming China were the most powerful and hegemonic states.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] The Renaissance in Italy and Europe saw the emergence of important artists, authors and scientists, and led to the foundation of important subjects which include accounting and political science.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] Copernicus proposed the heliocentric universe, which was met with strong resistance, and Tycho Brahe refuted the theory of celestial spheres through observational measurement of the 1572 appearance of a Milky Way supernova.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] These events directly challenged the long-held notion of an immutable universe supported by Ptolemy and Aristotle, and led to major revolutions in astronomy and science.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] Galileo Galilei became a champion of the new sciences, invented the first thermometer and made substantial contributions in the fields of physics and astronomy, becoming a major figure in the Scientific Revolution in Europe.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] Spain and Portugal colonized large parts of Central and South America, followed by France and England in Northern America and the Lesser Antilles.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] The Portuguese became the masters of trade between Brazil, the coasts of Africa, and their possessions in the Indies, whereas the Spanish came to dominate the Greater Antilles, Mexico, Peru, and opened trade across the Pacific Ocean, linking the Americas with the Indies.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] English and French privateers began to practice persistent theft of Spanish and Portuguese treasures.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] This era of colonialism established mercantilism as the leading school of economic thought, where the economic system was viewed as a zero-sum game in which any gain by one party required a loss by another.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] The mercantilist doctrine encouraged the many intra-European wars of the period and arguably fueled European expansion and imperialism throughout the world until the 19th century or early 20th century.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] The Reformation in central and northern Europe gave a major blow to the authority of the papacy and the Catholic Church.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] In England, the British-Italian Alberico Gentili wrote the first book on public international law and divided secularism from canon law and Catholic theology.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] European politics became dominated by religious conflicts, with the groundwork for the epochal Thirty Years' War being laid towards the end of the century.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] In the Middle East, the Ottoman Empire continued to expand, with the sultan taking the title of caliph, while dealing with a resurgent Persia.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] Iran and Iraq were caught by a major popularity of the Shia sect of Islam under the rule of the Safavid dynasty of warrior-mystics, providing grounds for a Persia independent of the majority-Sunni Muslim world.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] In the Indian subcontinent, following the defeat of the Delhi Sultanate and Vijayanagara Empire, new powers emerged, the Sur Empire founded by Sher Shah Suri, Deccan sultanates, Rajput states, and the Mughal Empire by Emperor Babur, a direct descendant of Timur and Genghis Khan.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] His successors Humayun and Akbar, enlarged the empire to include most of South Asia.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] Japan suffered a severe civil war at this time, known as the Sengoku period, and emerged from it as a unified nation under Toyotomi Hideyoshi.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] China was ruled by the Ming dynasty, which was becoming increasingly isolationist, coming into conflict with Japan over the control of Korea as well as Japanese pirates.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] In Africa, Christianity had begun to spread in Central Africa and Southern Africa.
[src:early-modern-period/16th-century] Until the Scramble for Africa in the late 19th century, most of Africa was left uncolonized.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century-in-philosophy] This is a timeline of **philosophy in the 17th century**.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] The **17th century** lasted from January 1, 1601 (represented by the Roman numerals MDCI), to December 31, 1700 (MDCC).
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] From the mid-17th century, European politics were increasingly dominated by the Kingdom of France of Louis XIV, where royal power was solidified domestically in the civil war of the Fronde.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] The semi-feudal territorial French nobility was weakened and subjugated to the power of an absolute monarchy through the reinvention of the Palace of Versailles from a hunting lodge to a gilded prison, in which a greatly expanded royal court could be more easily kept under surveillance.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] With domestic peace assured, Louis XIV caused the borders of France to be expanded.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] It was during this century that the English monarch became increasingly involved in conflicts with the Parliament, which would culminate in the English civil war and an end to the dominance of the English monarchy.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] It was also a period of development of culture in general (especially theater, music, visual arts and philosophy).
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] Some of the greatest inventions took place in this century.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] It was during this period that the European colonization of the Americas began in earnest, including the exploitation of the silver deposits, which resulted in bouts of inflation as wealth was drawn into Europe.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] Also during this period, there would be a more intense European presence in Southeast Asia and East Asia (such as the colonization of Taiwan).
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] These foreign elements would contribute to a revolution in Ayutthaya.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] The Mataram Sultanate and the Aceh Sultanate would be the major powers of the region, especially during the first half of the century.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] In the Islamic world, the gunpowder empires – the Ottoman, Safavid, and Mughal – grew in strength as well.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] The southern half of India would see the decline of the Deccan Sultanates and extinction of the Vijayanagara Empire.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] The Dutch would colonize Ceylon and endure hostilities with Kandy.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] The end of the 17th century saw the first major surrender of Ottoman territory in Europe when the Treaty of Karlowitz ceded most of Hungary to the Habsburgs in 1699.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] In Japan, Tokugawa Ieyasu established the Tokugawa shogunate at the beginning of the century, beginning the Edo period; the isolationist Sakoku policy began in the 1630s and lasted until the 19th century.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] In China, the collapsing Ming dynasty was challenged by a series of conquests led by the Manchu warlord Nurhaci, which were consolidated by his son Hong Taiji and finally consummated by his grandson, the Shunzhi Emperor, founder of the Qing dynasty.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] Qing China spent decades of this century with economic problems (results of civil wars between the Qing and former Ming dynasty loyalists), only recovering well at the end of the century.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] The greatest military conflicts of the century were the Thirty Years' War, Dutch–Portuguese War, the Great Turkish War, the Nine Years' War, Mughal–Safavid Wars, and the Qing annexation of the Ming.
[src:early-modern-period/17th-century] Major changes in philosophy and science take place, often characterized as the Scientific Revolution.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] The **18th century** lasted from 1 January 1701 (represented by the Roman numerals MDCCI) to 31 December 1800 (MDCCC).
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] During the 18th century, elements of Enlightenment thinking culminated in the Atlantic Revolutions.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] Revolutions began to challenge the legitimacy of monarchical and aristocratic power structures.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] The Industrial Revolution began mid-century, leading to radical changes in human society and the environment.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] The European colonization of the Americas and other parts of the world intensified and associated mass migrations of people grew in size as part of the Age of Sail.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] During the century, slave trading expanded across the shores of the Atlantic Ocean, while declining in Russia and China.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] Western historians have occasionally defined the 18th century otherwise for the purposes of their work.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] For example, the "short" 18th century may be defined as 1715–1789, denoting the period of time between the death of Louis XIV of France and the start of the French Revolution, with an emphasis on directly interconnected events.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] To historians who expand the century to include larger historical movements, the "long" 18th century may run from the Glorious Revolution of 1688 to the Battle of Waterloo in 1815 or even later.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] France was the dominant world power in Europe from 1659, after it defeated Spain, until 1815, when it was defeated by Britain and its coalitions following the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In Europe, philosophers ushered in the Age of Enlightenment.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] This period coincided with the French Revolution of 1789 and was later compromised by the excesses of the Reign of Terror.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] At first, many monarchies of Europe embraced Enlightenment ideals, but in the wake of the French Revolution they feared loss of power and formed broad coalitions to oppose the French Republic in the French Revolutionary Wars.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] Various conflicts throughout the century, including the War of the Spanish Succession and the Seven Years' War, saw Great Britain triumph over its rivals to become the preeminent power in Europe.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] However, Britain's attempts to exert its authority over the Thirteen Colonies became a catalyst for the American Revolution.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] The 18th century also marked the end of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth as an independent state.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] Its semi-democratic government system was not robust enough to prevent partition by the neighboring states of Austria, Prussia, and Russia.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In West Asia, Nader Shah led Persia in successful military campaigns.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] The Ottoman Empire experienced a period of peace, taking no part in European wars from 1740 to 1768.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] As a result, the empire was not exposed to Europe's military improvements during the Seven Years' War.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] The Ottoman military consequently lagged behind and suffered several defeats against Russia in the second half of the century.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In South Asia, the death of Mughal emperor Aurangzeb was followed by the expansion of the Maratha Confederacy and an increasing level of European influence and control in the region.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In 1739, Persian emperor Nader Shah invaded and plundered Delhi, the capital of the Mughal Empire.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] Later, his general Ahmad Shah Durrani scored another victory against the Marathas, the then dominant power in India, in the Third Battle of Panipat in 1761.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] By the middle of the century, the British East India Company began to conquer eastern India, and by the end of the century, the Anglo-Mysore Wars against Tipu Sultan and his father Hyder Ali, led to Company rule over the south.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In East Asia, the century was marked by the High Qing era, a period characterized by significant cultural and territorial expansion.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] This period also experienced relative peace and prosperity, allowing for societal growth, increasing literacy rates, flourishing trade, and consolidating imperial power across the vast Qing dynasty's territories.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] Conversely, the continual seclusion policy of the Tokugawa shogunate also brought a peaceful era called Pax Tokugawa and experienced a flourishment of the arts as well as scientific knowledge and advancements, which were introduced to Japan through the Dutch port of Nagasaki.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In Southeast Asia, the Konbaung–Ayutthaya Wars and the Tây Sơn Wars broke out while the Dutch East India Company established increasing levels of control over the Mataram Sultanate.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In Africa, the Ethiopian Empire underwent the Zemene Mesafint, a period when the country was ruled by a class of regional noblemen and the emperor was merely a figurehead.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] The Atlantic slave trade also saw the continued involvement of states such as the Oyo Empire.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In Oceania, the European colonization of Australia and New Zealand began during the late half of the century.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In the Americas, the United States declared its independence from Great Britain.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In 1776, Thomas Jefferson wrote the Declaration of Independence.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] In 1789, George Washington was inaugurated as the first president.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] Benjamin Franklin traveled to Europe where he was hailed as an inventor.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] Examples of his inventions include the lightning rod and bifocal glasses.
[src:early-modern-period/18th-century] Túpac Amaru II led an uprising that sought to end Spanish colonial rule in Peru.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The **19th century** began on 1 January 1801 (represented by the Roman numerals MDCCCI), and ended on 31 December 1900 (MCM).
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] It was the 9th century of the 2nd millennium.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] It was characterized by vast social upheaval.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Slavery was abolished in much of Europe and the Americas.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] A few decades later, the Second Industrial Revolution led to ever more massive urbanization and much higher levels of productivity, profit, and prosperity, a pattern that continued into the 20th century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Catholic Church, in response to the growing influence and power of modernism, secularism and materialism, formed the First Vatican Council in the late 19th century to deal with such problems and confirm certain Catholic doctrines as dogma.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Religious missionaries were sent from the Americas and Europe to Asia, Africa and the Middle East.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In the Middle East, it was an era of change and reform.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires fell into decline and European imperialism brought much of South Asia, Southeast Asia, and almost all of Africa under colonial rule.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Reformers were opposed at every turn by conservatives who strove to maintain the centuries-old Islamic laws and social order.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The 19th century also saw the collapse of the large Spanish, Portuguese, French and Mughal empires, which paved the way for the growing influence of the British, French, German, Russian, Austro-Hungarian, Italian, and Japanese empires along with the United States.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The defeat of France in the Napoleonic Wars marked the end of France’s status as the world superpower.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Britain took France’s status as the world superpower, the British and Russian empires expanded considerably, becoming two of the world's leading powers.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Russia expanded its territory to the Caucasus and Central Asia.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Ottoman Empire underwent a period of Westernization and reform known as the Tanzimat, vastly increasing its control over core territories in the Middle East.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] However, it remained in decline and became known as the sick man of Europe, losing territory in the Balkans and North Africa.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The remaining powers in the Indian subcontinent, such as the Maratha and Sikh empires, suffered a massive decline, and their dissatisfaction with the British East India Company's rule led to the Indian Rebellion of 1857 and the company's dissolution.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] India was later ruled directly by the British Crown through the establishment of the British Raj.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] During the post-Napoleonic era (after 1815), Britain enforced what became known as the Pax Britannica, which ushered in unprecedented globalization on a massive scale.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Britain's overseas possessions grew rapidly in the first half of the century, especially with the expansion of vast territories in Canada, Australia, India, and in the last two decades of the century in Africa.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] By the end of the 19th century, the British controlled a fifth of the world's land and a quarter of the world's population.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] After the Napoleonic Wars, France sought to rebuild its colonial empire, having lost most of its major overseas possessions to the British in the 17th and 18th centuries, including territories in North America (modern-day United States and Canada), French India, and much of the Caribbean.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] French expansion resumed in the 19th century, beginning with the conquest of Algeria in 1830 and the establishment of influence in Africa.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] French overseas possessions expanded gradually in the second half of the century, France significantly enlarged its colonial holdings, establishing French Indochina in Southeast Asia, French Polynesia, New Caledonia and the New Hebrides in Oceania and controlling over 40% of Africa.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] By the end of the century, Britain and France had colonized almost all of South Asia (British Raj), Southeast Asia (French Indochina), 80% of Africa and Oceania (Australia, New Zealand, French Polynesia, New Caledonia, New Hebrides).
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In East Asia, China under the Qing dynasty endured its century of humiliation by foreign powers with Britain and France carving up spheres of influences in China that lasted until the first half of the 20th century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The last surviving man and woman, respectively, verified to have been born in the 19th century were Jiroemon Kimura (1897–2013) and Nabi Tajima (1900–2018), both Japanese.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The first electronics appeared in the 19th century, with the introduction of the electric relay in 1835, the telegraph and its Morse code protocol in 1837, the first telephone call in 1876, and the first functional light bulb in 1878.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The 19th century was an era of rapidly accelerating scientific discovery and invention, with significant developments in the fields of mathematics, physics, chemistry, biology, electricity, and metallurgy that laid the groundwork for the technological advances of the 20th century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Industrial Revolution began in Great Britain and spread to continental Europe, North America, and Japan.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Victorian era was notorious for the employment of young children in factories and mines, as well as strict social norms regarding modesty and gender roles.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Japan embarked on a program of rapid modernization following the Meiji Restoration, before defeating China, under the Qing dynasty, in the First Sino-Japanese War.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Advances in medicine and the understanding of human anatomy and disease prevention took place in the 19th century, and were partly responsible for rapidly accelerating population growth in the Western world.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Europe's population doubled during the 19th century, from approximately 200 million to more than 400 million.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The introduction of railroads provided the first major advancement in land transportation for centuries, changing the way people lived and obtained goods, and fuelling major urbanization movements in countries across the globe.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Numerous cities worldwide surpassed populations of a million or more during this century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] London became the world's largest city and capital of the British Empire.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Its population increased from 1 million in 1800 to 6.7 million a century later.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The last remaining undiscovered landmasses of Earth, including vast expanses of interior Africa and Asia, were explored during this century, and with the exception of the extreme zones of the Arctic and Antarctic, accurate and detailed maps of the globe were available by the 1890s.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Liberalism became the pre-eminent reform movement in Europe.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Slavery was greatly reduced around the world.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Following a successful slave revolt in Haiti, Britain and France stepped up the battle against the Barbary pirates and succeeded in stopping their enslavement of Europeans.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The UK's Slavery Abolition Act 1833 charged the British Royal Navy with ending the global slave trade.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The first colonial empire in the century to abolish slavery was the British, who did so in 1834.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] America's Thirteenth Amendment following their Civil War abolished slavery there in 1865, and in Brazil slavery was abolished in 1888 (see abolitionism).
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Similarly, serfdom was abolished in Russia in 1861.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The 19th century was remarkable in the widespread formation of new settlement foundations which were particularly prevalent across North America and Australia, with a significant proportion of the two continents' largest cities being founded at some point in the century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Chicago in the United States and Melbourne in Australia were non-existent in the earliest decades but grew to become the 2nd largest cities in the United States and British Empire respectively by the end of the century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In the 19th century, approximately 70 million people left Europe, with most migrating to the United States.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The 19th century also saw the rapid creation, development, and codification of many sports, particularly in Britain and the United States.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Association football, rugby union, baseball, and many other sports were developed during the 19th century, while the British Empire facilitated the rapid spread of sports such as cricket to many different parts of the world.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Also, women's fashion was a very sensitive topic during this time, as women showing their ankles was viewed to be scandalous.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] It also marks the fall of the Ottoman rule of the Balkans which led to the creation of Serbia, Bulgaria, Montenegro, and Romania as a result of the second Russo-Turkish War, which in itself followed the great Crimean War.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Napoleonic Wars were a series of major conflicts from 1803 to 1815 pitting the French Empire and its allies, led by Napoleon I, against a fluctuating array of European powers formed into various coalitions, financed and usually led by the United Kingdom.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The wars stemmed from the unresolved disputes associated with the French Revolution and its resultant conflict.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In the aftermath of the French Revolution, Napoleon Bonaparte gained power in France in 1799.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1804, he crowned himself Emperor of the French.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1805, the French victory over an Austrian-Russian army at the Battle of Austerlitz ended the War of the Third Coalition.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] As a result of the Treaty of Pressburg, the Holy Roman Empire was dissolved.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In the Peninsular War, France unsuccessfully attempted to establish Joseph Bonaparte as King of Spain.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1812, the French invasion of Russia had massive French casualties, and was a turning point in the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1814, after defeat in the War of the Sixth Coalition, Napoleon abdicated and was exiled to Elba.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Later that year, he escaped exile and began the Hundred Days before finally being defeated at the Battle of Waterloo and exiled to Saint Helena, an island in the South Atlantic Ocean.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] After Napoleon's defeat, the Congress of Vienna was held to determine new national borders.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Concert of Europe attempted to preserve this settlement was established to preserve these borders, with limited impact.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Mexico and the majority of the countries in Central America and South America obtained independence from colonial overlords during the 19th century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1804, Haiti gained independence from France.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In Mexico, the Mexican War of Independence was a decade-long conflict that ended in Mexican independence in 1821.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Due to the Napoleonic Wars, the royal family of Portugal relocated to Brazil from 1808 to 1821, leading to Brazil having a separate monarchy from Portugal.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Federal Republic of Central America gained independence from Spain in 1821 and from Mexico in 1823.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] After several rebellions, by 1841 the federation had dissolved into the independent countries of Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua, and Costa Rica.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1830, the post-colonial nation of Gran Colombia dissolved and the nations of Colombia (including modern-day Panama), Ecuador, and Venezuela took its place.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Revolutions of 1848 were a series of political upheavals throughout Europe in 1848.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The revolutions were essentially democratic and liberal in nature, with the aim of removing the old monarchical structures and creating independent nation states.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The first revolution began in January in Sicily.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Revolutions then spread across Europe after a separate revolution began in France in February.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Over 50 countries were affected, but with no coordination or cooperation among their respective revolutionaries.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The abolitionism movement achieved success in the 19th century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Atlantic slave trade was abolished in the United States in 1808, and by the end of the century, almost every government had banned slavery.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Slavery Abolition Act 1833 banned slavery throughout the British Empire, and the Lei Áurea abolished slavery in Brazil in 1888.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Abolitionism in the United States continued until the end of the American Civil War.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Frederick Douglass and Harriet Tubman were two of many American abolitionists who helped win the fight against slavery.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Douglass was an articulate orator and incisive antislavery writer, while Tubman worked with a network of antislavery activists and safe houses known as the Underground Railroad.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The American Civil War took place from 1861 to 1865.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Eleven southern states seceded from the United States, largely over concerns related to slavery.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1863, President Abraham Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Lincoln issued a preliminary on September 22, 1862, warning that in all states still in rebellion (Confederacy) on January 1, 1863, he would declare their slaves "then, thenceforward, and forever free." He did so.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Thirteenth Amendment to the Constitution, ratified in 1865, officially abolished slavery in the entire country.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Lee surrendered at Appomattox Courthouse, Virginia, Lincoln was assassinated by actor and Confederate sympathizer John Wilkes Booth.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1817, the Principality of Serbia became suzerain from the Ottoman Empire, and in 1867, it passed a constitution that defined its independence from the Ottoman Empire.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1830, Greece became the first country to break away from the Ottoman Empire after the Greek War of Independence.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1831, the Bosnian Uprising against Ottoman rule occurred.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1831, The First Egyptian–Ottoman War (1831–1833) occurred, between the Ottoman Empire and Egypt brought about by Muhammad Ali Pasha's demand to the Sublime Porte for control of Greater Syria, as reward for aiding the Sultan during the Greek War of Independence.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] As a result, Egyptian forces temporarily gained control of Syria, advancing as far north as Kütahya.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1876, Bulgarians instigated the April Uprising against Ottoman rule.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Following the Russo-Turkish War, the Treaty of Berlin recognized the formal independence of Serbia, Montenegro, and Romania.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Taiping Rebellion was the bloodiest conflict of the 19th century, leading to the deaths of around 20–30 million people.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Its leader, Hong Xiuquan, declared himself the younger brother of Jesus Christ and developed a new Chinese religion known as the God Worshipping Society.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] After proclaiming the establishment of the Taiping Heavenly Kingdom in 1851, the Taiping army conquered a large part of China, capturing Nanjing in 1853.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1864, after the death of Hong Xiuquan, Qing forces recaptured Nanjing and ended the rebellion.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] During the Edo period, Japan largely pursued an isolationist foreign policy.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1853, United States Navy Commodore Matthew C.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Perry threatened the Japanese capital Edo with gunships, demanding that they agree to open trade.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] This led to the opening of trade relations between Japan and foreign countries, with the policy of Sakoku formally ended in 1854.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] By 1872, the Japanese government under Emperor Meiji had eliminated the *daimyō* system and established a strong central government.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Further reforms included the abolition of the samurai class, rapid industrialization and modernization of government, closely following European models.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In Africa, European exploration and technology led to the colonization of almost the entire continent by 1898.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] New medicines such as quinine and more advanced firearms allowed European nations to conquer native populations.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Motivations for the Scramble for Africa included national pride, desire for raw materials, and Christian missionary activity.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Britain seized control of Egypt to ensure control of the Suez Canal, but Ethiopia defeated Italy in the First Italo–Ethiopian War at the Battle of Adwa.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] France, Belgium, Portugal, and Germany also had substantial colonies.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Berlin Conference of 1884–1885 attempted to reach agreement on colonial borders in Africa, but disputes continued, both amongst European powers and in resistance by the native populations.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1867, diamonds were discovered in the Kimberley region of South Africa.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In 1886, gold was discovered in Transvaal.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] This led to colonization in Southern Africa by the British and business interests, led by Cecil Rhodes.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The 19th century saw the birth of science as a profession; the term **scientist** was coined in 1833 by William Whewell, which soon replaced the older term of **natural philosopher**.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Among the most influential ideas of the 19th century were those of Charles Darwin (alongside the independent researches of Alfred Russel Wallace), who in 1859 published the book *The Origin of Species*, which introduced the idea of evolution by natural selection.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Another important landmark in medicine and biology were the successful efforts to prove the germ theory of disease.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Following this, Louis Pasteur made the first vaccine against rabies, and also made many discoveries in the field of chemistry, including the asymmetry of crystals.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In chemistry, Dmitri Mendeleev, following the atomic theory of John Dalton, created the first periodic table of elements.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In physics, the experiments, theories and discoveries of Michael Faraday, André-Marie Ampère, James Clerk Maxwell, and their contemporaries led to the creation of electromagnetism as a new branch of science.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Thermodynamics led to an understanding of heat and the notion of energy was defined.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Other highlights include the discoveries unveiling the nature of atomic structure and matter, simultaneously with chemistry – and of new kinds of radiation.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In astronomy, the planet Neptune was discovered.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In mathematics, the notion of complex numbers finally matured and led to a subsequent analytical theory; they also began the use of hypercomplex numbers.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Karl Weierstrass and others carried out the arithmetization of analysis for functions of real and complex variables.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] It also saw rise to new progress in geometry beyond those classical theories of Euclid, after a period of nearly two thousand years.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The mathematical science of logic likewise had revolutionary breakthroughs after a similarly long period of stagnation.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] But the most important step in science at this time were the ideas formulated by the creators of electrical science.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Their work changed the face of physics and made possible for new technology to come about including a rapid spread in the use of electric illumination and power in the last two decades of the century and radio wave communication at the end of the 1890s.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] William Wordsworth and Samuel Taylor Coleridge are considered the initiators of the new school in England, while in the continent the German *Sturm und Drang* spreads its influence as far as Italy and Spain.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] French arts had been hampered by the Napoleonic Wars but subsequently developed rapidly.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Goncourts and Émile Zola in France and Giovanni Verga in Italy produce some of the finest naturalist novels.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Italian naturalist novels are especially important in that they give a social map of the new unified Italy to a people that until then had been scarcely aware of its ethnic and cultural diversity.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] There was a huge literary output during the 19th century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Some American literary writers, poets and novelists were: Walt Whitman, Mark Twain, Harriet Ann Jacobs, Nathaniel Hawthorne, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Herman Melville, Frederick Douglass, Harriet Beecher Stowe, Joel Chandler Harris, and Emily Dickinson to name a few.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] The Realism and Romanticism of the early 19th century gave way to Impressionism and Post-Impressionism in the later half of the century, with Paris being the dominant art capital of the world.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] In the United States the Hudson River School was prominent.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Sonata form matured during the Classical era to become the primary form of instrumental compositions throughout the 19th century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Much of the music from the 19th century was referred to as being in the Romantic style.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p01] Many great composers lived through this era such as Ludwig van Beethoven, Franz Liszt, Frédéric Chopin, Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky, and Richard Wagner.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p02] Born on 19 April 1897, Japanese Jiroemon Kimura died on 12 June 2013, marking the death of the last man verified to have been born in the century.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p02] Kimura remains to date the oldest verified man in history.
[src:early-modern-period/19th-century-p02] Subsequently, on 21 April 2018, Japanese Nabi Tajima (born 4 August 1900) died as the last person to verifiably have been born in the century.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Initially influenced by Toulouse-Lautrec, Gauguin, and other late-19th-century innovators, Pablo Picasso made his first cubist paintings based on Cézanne's idea that all depiction of nature can be reduced to three solids: cube, sphere, and cone.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With the painting *Les Demoiselles d'Avignon* (1907; see gallery) Picasso created a new and radical picture depicting a raw and primitive brothel scene with five prostitutes, violently painted women, reminiscent of African tribal masks and his own new proto-Cubist inventions.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism, exemplified by *Violin and Candlestick, Paris*, was jointly developed by Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque from about 1908 through 1912.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism was followed by Synthetic cubism, characterized by the introduction of different textures, surfaces, collage elements, papier collé and a large variety of merged subject matter.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the years between 1910 and the end of World War I and after the heyday of cubism, several movements emerged in Paris.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Giorgio de Chirico moved to Paris in July 1911, where he joined his brother Andrea (the poet and painter known as Alberto Savinio).
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Through his brother he met Pierre Laprade, a member of the jury at the Salon d'Automne, where he exhibited three of his dreamlike works: *Enigma of the Oracle*, *Enigma of an Afternoon* and *Self-Portrait*.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During 1913 he exhibited his work at the Salon des Indépendants and Salon d’Automne, where his work was noticed by Pablo Picasso, Guillaume Apollinaire, and others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His compelling and mysterious paintings are considered instrumental to the early beginnings of Surrealism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Song of Love* (1914) is one of the most famous works by de Chirico and is an early example of the surrealist style, though it was painted ten years before the movement was "founded" by André Breton in 1924.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Modern painting influenced all the visual arts, from Modernist architecture and design, to avant-garde film, theatre and modern dance, and became an experimental laboratory for the expression of visual experience, from photography and concrete poetry to advertising art and fashion.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Van Gogh's paintings exerted great influence upon 20th-century Expressionism, as can be seen in the work of the Fauves, Die Brücke (a group led by German painter Ernst Kirchner), and the Expressionism of Edvard Munch, Egon Schiele, Marc Chagall, Amedeo Modigliani, Chaïm Soutine, and others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Wassily Kandinsky, a Russian painter, printmaker and art theorist, is generally considered the first important painter of modern abstract art.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As an early modernist, in search of new modes of visual expression, and spiritual expression, he theorized—as did contemporary occultists and theosophists—that pure visual abstraction had corollary vibrations with sound and music.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] They posited that pure abstraction could express pure spirituality.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His earliest abstractions were generally titled (as the example in the above gallery) *Composition VII*, making connection to the work of the composers of music.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kandinsky included many of his theories about abstract art in his book *Concerning the Spiritual in Art*.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Piet Mondrian's art was also related to his spiritual and philosophical studies.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1908 he became interested in the theosophical movement launched by Helena Petrovna Blavatsky in the late 19th century.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Blavatsky believed that it was possible to attain a knowledge of nature more profound than that provided by empirical means, and much of Mondrian's work for the rest of his life was inspired by his search for that spiritual knowledge.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other major pioneers of early abstraction include Swedish painter Hilma af Klint, Russian painter Kazimir Malevich, and Swiss painter Paul Klee.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Robert Delaunay was a French artist who is associated with Orphism, (reminiscent of a link between pure abstraction and cubism).
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His later works were more abstract, reminiscent of Paul Klee.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His key contributions to abstract painting refer to his bold use of color, and a clear love of experimentation of both depth and tone.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] At the invitation of Kandinsky, Delaunay and his wife the artist Sonia Delaunay, joined The Blue Rider (Der Blaue Reiter), a Munich-based group of abstract artists, in 1911, and his art took a turn to the abstract.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Still other important pioneers of abstract painting include Czech painter, František Kupka as well as American artists Stanton Macdonald-Wright and Morgan Russell who, in 1912, founded Synchromism, an art movement that closely resembles Orphism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Les Fauves (French for *The Wild Beasts*) were early-20th-century painters, experimenting with freedom of expression through color.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name was given, humorously and not as a compliment, to the group by art critic Louis Vauxcelles.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism was a short-lived and loose grouping of artists whose works emphasized painterly qualities and the imaginative use of deep color over the representational values.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvists made the subject of the painting easy to read and exaggerated perspectives.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The leaders of the movement were Henri Matisse and André Derain—friendly rivals of a sort, each with his own followers.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ultimately Matisse became the *yang* to Picasso's *yin* in the 20th century.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvist painters included Albert Marquet, Charles Camoin, Maurice de Vlaminck, Raoul Dufy, Othon Friesz, the Dutch painter Kees van Dongen, and Picasso's partner in Cubism, Georges Braque amongst others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism, as a movement, had no concrete theories, and was short lived, beginning in 1905 and ending in 1907.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse was seen as the leader of the movement, due to his seniority in age and prior self-establishment in the academic art world.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse, *The Green Line* (above), caused a sensation in Paris when it was first exhibited.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He said he wanted to create art to delight; art as a decoration was his purpose and it can be said that his use of bright colors tries to maintain serenity of composition.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1906 at the suggestion of his dealer Ambroise Vollard, André Derain went to London and produced a series of paintings like *Charing Cross Bridge, London* (above) in the Fauvist style, paraphrasing the famous series by the Impressionist painter Claude Monet.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] By 1907 Fauvism no longer was a shocking new movement, soon it was replaced by Cubism on the critics radar screen as the latest new development in Contemporary Art of the time.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter was a German movement lasting from 1911 to 1914, fundamental to Expressionism, along with Die Brücke, a group of German expressionist artists formed in Dresden in 1905.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Founding members of Die Brücke were Fritz Bleyl, Erich Heckel, Ernst Ludwig Kirchner and Karl Schmidt-Rottluff.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Later members included Max Pechstein, Otto Mueller and others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This was a seminal group, which in due course had a major impact on the evolution of modern art in the 20th century and created the style of Expressionism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter lacked a central artistic manifesto, but was centered around Kandinsky and Marc.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists Gabriele Münter and Paul Klee were also involved.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name of the movement comes from a painting by Kandinsky created in 1903.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is also claimed that the name could have derived from Marc's enthusiasm for horses and Kandinsky's love of the colour blue.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] For Kandinsky, *blue* is the colour of spirituality: the darker the blue, the more it awakens human desire for the eternal.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Marcel Duchamp came to international prominence in the wake of the New York City Armory Show in 1913 where his *Nude Descending a Staircase* became the *cause célèbre*.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He subsequently created *The Bride Stripped Bare by Her Bachelors, Even, Large Glass*.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Large Glass* pushed the art of painting to radical new limits being part painting, part collage, part construction.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp (who was soon to renounce artmaking for chess) became closely associated with the Dada movement that began in neutral Zürich, Switzerland, during World War I and peaked from 1916 to 1920.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The movement primarily involved visual arts, literature (poetry, art manifestoes, art theory), theatre, and graphic design, and concentrated its anti war politic through a rejection of the prevailing standards in art through anti-art cultural works.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Francis Picabia, Man Ray, Kurt Schwitters, Tristan Tzara, Hans Richter, Jean Arp, Sophie Taeuber-Arp, along with Duchamp and many others are associated with the Dadaist movement.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp and several Dadaists are also associated with Surrealism, the movement that dominated European painting in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1924 André Breton published the *Surrealist Manifesto.* The Surrealist movement in painting became synonymous with the avant-garde and which featured artists whose works varied from the abstract to the super-realist.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With works on paper like *Machine Turn Quickly* (above) Francis Picabia continued his involvement in the Dada movement through 1919 in Zürich and Paris, before breaking away from it after developing an interest in Surrealist art.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Yves Tanguy, René Magritte and Salvador Dalí are particularly known for their realistic depictions of dream imagery and fantastic manifestations of the imagination.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Joan Miró's *The Tilled Field* of 1923–1924 verges on abstraction, this early painting of a complex of objects and figures, and arrangements of sexually active characters; was Miró's first Surrealist masterpiece.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The more abstract Joan Miró, Jean Arp, André Masson, and Max Ernst were very influential, especially in the United States during the 1940s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 1930s, Surrealism continued to become more visible to the public at large.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] A Surrealist group developed in Britain and, according to Breton, their 1936 London International Surrealist Exhibition was a high-water mark of the period and became the model for international exhibitions.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Surrealist groups in Japan, and especially in Latin America, the Caribbean and in Mexico produced innovative and original works.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí and Magritte created some of the most widely recognized images of the movement.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1928/1929 painting *This Is Not A Pipe* by Magritte is the subject of a Michel Foucault 1973 book, *This is not a Pipe* (English edition, 1991), that discusses the painting and its paradox.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí joined the group in 1929, and participated in the rapid establishment of the visual style between 1930 and 1935.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Evocations of time and its compelling mystery and absurdity.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Max Ernst studied philosophy and psychology in Bonn and was interested in the alternative realities experienced by the insane.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His paintings, such as *Murdering Airplane* (1920), may have been inspired by the psychoanalyst Sigmund Freud's study of the delusions of a paranoiac, Daniel Paul Schreber.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Freud identified Schreber's fantasy of becoming a woman as a *castration complex*.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The central image of two pairs of legs refers to Schreber's hermaphroditic desires.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ernst's inscription on the back of the painting reads: *The picture is curious because of its symmetry.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s André Masson's work was enormously influential in helping the young artist Joan Miró find his roots in the new Surrealist painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Miró acknowledged in letters to his dealer Pierre Matisse the importance of Masson as an example to him in his early years in Paris.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Long after personal, political and professional tensions have fragmented the Surrealist group into thin air and ether, Magritte, Miró, Dalí and the other Surrealists continue to define a visual program in the arts.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other prominent surrealist artists include Giorgio de Chirico, Méret Oppenheim, Toyen, Grégoire Michonze, Roberto Matta, Kay Sage, Leonora Carrington, Dorothea Tanning, and Leonor Fini among others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s and the 1930s and the Great Depression, the European art scene was characterized by Surrealism, late Cubism, the Bauhaus, De Stijl, Dada, Neue Sachlichkeit, and Expressionism; and was occupied by masterful modernist color painters like Henri Matisse and Pierre Bonnard.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Scene painting and the Social Realism and Regionalism movements that contained both political and social commentary dominated the art world in the USA.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, Grant Wood, George Tooker, John Steuart Curry, Reginald Marsh, and others became prominent.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo's Symbolist works also relate strongly to Surrealism and to the Magic Realism movement in literature.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The psychological drama in many of Kahlo's self-portraits (above) underscore the vitality and relevance of her paintings to artists in the 21st century.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Germany Neue Sachlichkeit ("New Objectivity") emerged as Max Beckmann, Otto Dix, George Grosz and others associated with the Berlin Secession politicized their paintings.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The work of these artists grew out of expressionism, and was a response to the political tensions of the Weimar Republic, and was often sharply satirical.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Diego Rivera is perhaps best known by the public for his 1933 mural, *Man at the Crossroads*, in the lobby of the RCA Building at Rockefeller Center.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] When his patron Nelson Rockefeller discovered that the mural included a portrait of Lenin and other communist imagery, he fired Rivera, and the unfinished work was eventually destroyed by Rockefeller's staff.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The film *Cradle Will Rock* includes a dramatization of the controversy.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo (Rivera's wife's) works are often characterized by their stark portrayals of pain.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Of her 143 paintings 55 are self-portraits, which frequently incorporate symbolic portrayals of her physical and psychological wounds.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kahlo was deeply influenced by indigenous Mexican culture, which is apparent in her paintings' bright colors and dramatic symbolism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Christian and Jewish themes are often depicted in her work as well; she combined elements of the classic religious Mexican tradition—which were often bloody and violent—with surrealist renderings.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] While her paintings are not overtly Christian—she was an avowed communist—they certainly contain elements of the macabre Mexican Christian style of religious paintings.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s radical leftist politics characterized many of the artists connected to Surrealism, including Pablo Picasso.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] On 26 April 1937, during the Spanish Civil War, the Basque town of Gernika was the scene of the "Bombing of Gernika" by the Condor Legion of Nazi Germany's Luftwaffe.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The Germans were attacking to support the efforts of Francisco Franco to overthrow the Basque Government and the Spanish Republican government.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The town was devastated, though the Biscayan assembly and the Oak of Gernika survived.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted his mural sized *Guernica* to commemorate the horrors of the bombing.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In its final form, *Guernica* is an immense black and white, 3.5 metre (11 ft) tall and 7.8 metre (23 ft) wide mural painted in oil.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The mural presents a scene of death, violence, brutality, suffering, and helplessness without portraying their immediate causes.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The choice to paint in black and white contrasts with the intensity of the scene depicted and invokes the immediacy of a newspaper photograph.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted the mural sized painting called *Guernica* in protest of the bombing.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting was first exhibited in Paris in 1937, then Scandinavia, then London in 1938 and finally in 1939 at Picasso's request the painting was sent to the United States in an extended loan (for safekeeping) at MoMA.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting went on a tour of museums throughout the U.S. until its final return to the Museum of Modern Art in New York City where it was exhibited for nearly thirty years.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Finally in accord with Picasso's wish to give the painting to the people of Spain as a gift, it was sent to Spain in 1981.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the Great Depression of the 1930s, through the years of World War II American art was characterized by Social Realism and American Scene Painting (as seen above) in the work of Grant Wood, Edward Hopper, Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, and several others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Nighthawks* (1942) is a painting by Edward Hopper that portrays people sitting in a downtown diner late at night.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is not only Hopper's most famous painting, but one of the most recognizable in American art.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is currently in the collection of the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The scene was inspired by a diner (since demolished) in Greenwich Village, Hopper's home neighborhood in Manhattan.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Hopper began painting it immediately after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After this event there was a large feeling of gloominess over the country, a feeling that is portrayed in the painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The urban street is empty outside the diner, and inside none of the three patrons is apparently looking or talking to the others but instead is lost in their own thoughts.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This portrayal of modern urban life as empty or lonely is a common theme throughout Hopper's work.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1940s in New York City heralded the triumph of American abstract expressionism, a modernist movement that combined lessons learned from Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Surrealism, Joan Miró, Cubism, Fauvism, and early Modernism via great teachers in America like Hans Hofmann and John D.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American artists benefited from the presence of Piet Mondrian, Fernand Léger, Max Ernst and the André Breton group, Pierre Matisse's gallery, and Peggy Guggenheim's The Art of This Century Gallery, as well as other factors.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Abstract Expressionism got its name in 1946 from the art critic Robert Coates.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is seen as combining the emotional intensity and self-denial of the German Expressionists with the anti-figurative aesthetic of the European abstract schools such as Futurism, the Bauhaus and Synthetic Cubism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract Expressionism, Action painting, and Color Field painting are synonymous with the New York School.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Technically Surrealism was an important predecessor for Abstract expressionism with its emphasis on spontaneous, automatic or subconscious creation.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Jackson Pollock's dripping paint onto a canvas laid on the floor is a technique that has its roots in the work of André Masson.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Another important early manifestation of what came to be abstract expressionism is the work of American Northwest artist Mark Tobey, especially his "white writing" canvases, which, though generally not large in scale, anticipate the "all over" look of Pollock's drip paintings.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Additionally, abstract expressionism has an image of being rebellious, anarchic, highly idiosyncratic and, some feel, rather nihilistic.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In practice, the term is applied to any number of artists working (mostly) in New York who had quite different styles, and even applied to work which is not especially abstract nor expressionist.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Pollock's energetic "action paintings", with their "busy" feel, are different both technically and aesthetically, to the violent and grotesque *Women* series of Willem de Kooning.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As seen above in the gallery *Woman V* is one of a series of six paintings made by de Kooning between 1950 and 1953 that depict a three-quarter-length female figure.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He began the first of these paintings, *Woman I* collection: The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, in June 1950, repeatedly changing and painting out the image until January or February 1952, when the painting was abandoned unfinished.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The art historian Meyer Schapiro saw the painting in de Kooning's studio soon afterwards and encouraged the artist to persist.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Kooning's response was to begin three other paintings on the same theme; *Woman II*, The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, *Woman III*, Tehran Museum of Contemporary Art, *Woman IV*, Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the summer of 1952, spent at East Hampton, de Kooning further explored the theme through drawings and pastels.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He may have finished work on *Woman I* by the end of June, or possibly as late as November 1952, and probably the other three women pictures were concluded at much the same time.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Woman series* are decidedly figurative paintings.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Both Hans Hofmann and Robert Motherwell (gallery) can be comfortably described as practitioners of action painting and Color field painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism has many stylistic similarities to the Russian artists of the early twentieth century such as Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although it is true that spontaneity or of the impression of spontaneity characterized many of the abstract expressionists works, most of these paintings involved careful planning, especially since their large size demanded it.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] An exception might be the drip paintings of Pollock.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Why this style gained mainstream acceptance in the 1950s is a matter of debate.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Social realism had been the mainstream in the 1930s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It had been influenced not only by the Great Depression but also by the Social Realists of Mexico such as David Alfaro Siqueiros and Diego Rivera.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The political climate after World War II did not long tolerate the social protests of those painters.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism arose during World War II and began to be showcased during the early 1940s at galleries in New York like The Art of This Century Gallery.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The late 1940s through the mid-1950s ushered in the McCarthy era.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It was after World War II and a time of political conservatism and extreme artistic censorship in the United States.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Some people have conjectured that since the subject matter was often totally abstract, Abstract expressionism became a safe strategy for artists to pursue this style.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract art could be seen as apolitical.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Or if the art was political, the message was largely for the insiders.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] However those theorists are in the minority.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As the first truly original school of painting in America, Abstract expressionism demonstrated the vitality and creativity of the country in the post-war years, as well as its ability (or need) to develop an aesthetic sense that was not constrained by the European standards of beauty.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although Abstract expressionism spread quickly throughout the United States, the major centers of this style were New York City and California, especially in the New York School, and the San Francisco Bay area.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionist paintings share certain characteristics, including the use of large canvases, an "all-over" approach, in which the whole canvas is treated with equal importance (as opposed to the center being of more interest than the edges).
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The canvas as the *arena* became a credo of Action painting, while the *integrity of the picture plane* became a credo of the Color Field painters.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1950s, Color Field painting initially referred to a particular type of abstract expressionism, especially the work of Mark Rothko, Clyfford Still, Barnett Newman, Robert Motherwell and Adolph Gottlieb.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It essentially involved abstract paintings with large, flat expanses of color that expressed the sensual, and visual feelings and properties of large areas of nuanced surface.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Art critic Clement Greenberg perceived Color Field painting as related to but different from Action painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The overall expanse and gestalt of the work of the early color field painters speaks of an almost religious experience, awestruck in the face of an expanding universe of sensuality, color and surface.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Clyfford Still, Mark Rothko, Hans Hofmann, Morris Louis, Jules Olitski, Kenneth Noland, Helen Frankenthaler, Larry Zox, and others often used greatly reduced references to nature, and they painted with a highly articulated and psychological use of color.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In general these artists eliminated recognizable imagery.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In *Mountains and Sea,* from 1952, a seminal work of Colorfield painting by Helen Frankenthaler the artist used the stain technique for the first time.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Europe there was the continuation of Surrealism, Cubism, Dada and the works of Matisse.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Also in Europe, Tachisme (the European equivalent to Abstract expressionism) and Informalism took hold of the newest generation.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Serge Poliakoff, Nicolas de Staël, Georges Mathieu, Vieira da Silva, Jean Dubuffet, Yves Klein and Pierre Soulages among others are considered important figures in post-war European painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Eventually abstract painting in America evolved into movements such as Neo-Dada, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, Neo-expressionism and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As a response to the tendency toward abstraction imagery emerged through various new movements, notably Pop art.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s through the 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Abstract Expressionism, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, and Lyrical abstraction.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other artists reacted as a response to the tendency toward abstraction allowing imagery to continue through various new contexts like the Bay Area Figurative Movement in the 1950s and new forms of expressionism from the 1940s through the 1960s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Italy during this time, Giorgio Morandi was the foremost still life painter, exploring a wide variety of approaches to depicting everyday bottles and kitchen implements.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 20th century many painters practiced Realism and used expressive imagery; practicing landscape and figurative painting with contemporary subjects and solid technique, and unique expressivity like Milton Avery, John D.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham, Fairfield Porter, Edward Hopper, Andrew Wyeth, Balthus, Francis Bacon, Frank Auerbach, Lucian Freud, Leon Kossoff, Philip Pearlstein, Willem de Kooning, Arshile Gorky, Grace Hartigan, Robert De Niro, Sr., Elaine de Kooning and others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Pierre Bonnard, Georges Braque, and other 20th-century masters.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The figurative work of Francis Bacon, Frida Kahlo, Edward Hopper, Lucian Freud Andrew Wyeth and others served as a kind of alternative to abstract expressionism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] One of the most well-known images in 20th-century American art is Wyeth's painting, *Christina's World*, currently in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art in New York City.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It depicts a woman lying on the ground in a treeless, mostly tawny field, looking up at and crawling towards a gray house on the horizon; a barn and various other small outbuildings are adjacent to the house.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This tempera work, done in a realist style, is nearly always on display at the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Arshile Gorky's portrait of what may be his friend Willem de Kooning (left) is an example of the evolution of Abstract Expressionism from the context of figure painting, cubism and surrealism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with his friends de Kooning and John D.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham Gorky created bio-morphically shaped and abstracted figurative compositions that by the 1940s evolved into totally abstract paintings.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Gorky's work seems to be a careful analysis of memory, emotion and shape, using line and color to express feeling and nature.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After World War II the term School of Paris often referred to Tachisme, the European equivalent of American Abstract expressionism and those artists are also related to Cobra.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1952 Michel Tapié authored the book *Un Autre art* which gave name and voice to Informalism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Important proponents being Jean Dubuffet, Pierre Soulages, Nicolas de Staël, Hans Hartung, Serge Poliakoff, and Georges Mathieu, among several others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the early 1950s Dubuffet (who was always a figurative artist), and de Staël, abandoned abstraction, and returned to imagery via figuration and landscape.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Staël 's work was quickly recognised within the post-war art world, and he became one of the most influential artists of the 1950s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Much of de Staël 's late work – in particular his thinned, and diluted oil on canvas abstract landscapes of the mid-1950s predicts Color Field painting and Lyrical Abstraction of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Nicolas de Staël's bold and intensely vivid color in his last paintings predict the direction of much of contemporary painting that came after him including Pop art of the 1960s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art in America was to a large degree initially inspired by the works of Jasper Johns, Larry Rivers, and Robert Rauschenberg.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although the paintings of Gerald Murphy, Stuart Davis and Charles Demuth during the 1920s and 1930s set the table for Pop art in America.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In New York City during the mid-1950s Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns created works of art that at first seemed to be continuations of Abstract expressionist painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Actually their works and the work of Larry Rivers, were radical departures from abstract expressionism especially in the use of banal and literal imagery and the inclusion and the combining of mundane materials into their work.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Eventually by 1963 the movement came to be known worldwide as Pop art.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art is exemplified by artists: Andy Warhol, Claes Oldenburg, Wayne Thiebaud, James Rosenquist, Jim Dine, Tom Wesselmann and Roy Lichtenstein among others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein used oil and Magna paint in his best known works, such as *Drowning Girl* (1963), which was appropriated from the lead story in DC Comics' *Secret Hearts* #83.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] (*Drowning Girl* now is in the collection of Museum of Modern Art, New York.) Also featuring thick outlines, bold colors and Ben-Day dots to represent certain colors, as if created by photographic reproduction.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein would say of his own work: Abstract Expressionists "put things down on the canvas and responded to what they had done, to the color positions and sizes.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In October 1962 the Sidney Janis Gallery mounted *The New Realists* the first major Pop art group exhibition in an uptown art gallery in New York City.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Sidney Janis mounted the exhibition in a 57th Street storefront near his gallery at 15 E.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The show sent shockwaves through the New York School and reverberated worldwide.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in the fall of 1962 a historically important and ground-breaking *New Painting of Common Objects* exhibition of Pop art, curated by Walter Hopps at the Pasadena Art Museum sent shock waves across the Western United States.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Campbell's Soup Cans* (sometimes referred to as *32 Campbell's Soup Cans*) is the title of an Andy Warhol work of art that was produced in 1962.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It consists of thirty-two canvases, each measuring 20 inches in height x 16 inches in width (50.8 x 40.6 cm) and each consisting of a painting of a Campbell's Soup can—one of each canned soup variety the company offered at the time.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The individual paintings were produced with a semi-mechanised silkscreen process, using a non-painterly style.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] They helped usher in Pop art as a major art movement that relied on themes from popular culture.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works by Andy Warhol are repetitive and they are made in a non-painterly commercial manner.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in England in 1956 the term *Pop Art* was used by Lawrence Alloway for paintings that celebrated consumerism of the post World War II era.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement rejected Abstract expressionism and its focus on the hermeneutic and psychological interior, in favor of art which depicted, and often celebrated material consumer culture, advertising, and iconography of the mass production age.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The early works of David Hockney whose paintings emerged from England during the 1960s like *A Bigger Splash,* and the works of Richard Hamilton, Peter Blake, and Eduardo Paolozzi, are considered seminal examples in the movement.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in the downtown scene in New York's East Village 10th Street galleries artists were formulating an American version of Pop art.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Claes Oldenburg had his storefront, and the Green Gallery on 57th Street began to show Tom Wesselmann and James Rosenquist.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later Leo Castelli exhibited other American artists including the bulk of the careers of Andy Warhol and Roy Lichtenstein and his use of Benday dots, a technique used in commercial reproduction and seen in ordinary comic books and in paintings like *Drowning Girl*, 1963, in the gallery above.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] There is a connection between the radical works of Duchamp, and Man Ray, the rebellious Dadaists – with a sense of humor; and Pop Artists like Alex Katz (who became known for his parodies of portrait photography and suburban life), Claes Oldenburg, Andy Warhol, Roy Lichtenstein and the others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1950s and 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] 1),* 1963, Oil on canvas, 60 1/4 x 50 1/2 inches, collection: San Francisco Museum of Modern Art), and later in the 1970s Neo-expressionism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bay Area Figurative Movement of whom David Park, Elmer Bischoff, Nathan Oliveira and Richard Diebenkorn whose painting *Cityscape 1,* 1963 is a typical example were influential members flourished during the 1950s and 1960s in California.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Younger painters practiced the use of imagery in new and radical ways.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Yves Klein, Martial Raysse, Niki de Saint Phalle, David Hockney, Alex Katz, Antoni Tàpies, Malcolm Morley, Ralph Goings, Audrey Flack, Richard Estes, Chuck Close, Susan Rothenberg, Eric Fischl, John Baeder, and Vija Celmins were a few who became prominent between the 1960s and the 1980s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fairfield Porter was largely self-taught, and produced representational work in the midst of the Abstract Expressionist movement.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His subjects were primarily landscapes, domestic interiors and portraits of family, friends and fellow artists, many of them affiliated with the New York School of writers, including John Ashbery, Frank O'Hara, and James Schuyler.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many of his paintings were set in or around the family summer house on Great Spruce Head Island, Maine.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-Dada is a movement that started in the 1950s and 1960s and was related to Abstract expressionism only with imagery.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Featuring the emergence of combined manufactured items, with artist materials, moving away from previous conventions of painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This trend in art is exemplified by the work of Jasper Johns and Robert Rauschenberg, whose "combines" in the 1950s were forerunners of Pop Art and Installation art, and made use of the assemblage of large physical objects, including stuffed animals, birds and commercial photography.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s and 1970s abstract painting continued to develop in America through varied styles.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Geometric abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Color Field painting and minimal painting, were some interrelated directions for advanced abstract painting as well as some other new movements.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Morris Louis was an important pioneer in advanced Colorfield painting, his work can serve as a bridge between Abstract expressionism, Colorfield painting, and Minimal Art.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Two influential teachers Josef Albers and Hans Hofmann introduced a new generation of American artists to their advanced theories of color and space.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Josef Albers is best remembered for his work as a Geometric abstractionist painter and theorist.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Most famous are the hundreds of paintings and prints that make up the series *Homage to the Square*.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this rigorous series, begun in 1949, Albers explored chromatic interactions with flat colored squares arranged concentrically on the canvas.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Albers' theories on art and education were formative for the next generation of artists.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His own paintings form the foundation of both hard-edge painting and Op art.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many Geometric abstract artists, minimalists, and Hard-edge painters elected to use the edges of the image to define the shape of the painting rather than accepting the rectangular format.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In fact, the use of the shaped canvas is primarily associated with paintings of the 1960s and 1970s that are coolly abstract, formalistic, geometrical, objective, rationalistic, clean-lined, brashly sharp-edged, or minimalist in character.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bykert Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Minimalism and shaped canvas painting in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In 1965, an exhibition called *The Responsive Eye*, curated by William C.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Seitz, was held at the Museum of Modern Art, in New York City.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The works shown were wide-ranging, encompassing the Minimalism of Frank Stella, the Op art of Larry Poons, the work of Alexander Liberman, alongside the masters of the Op Art movement: Victor Vasarely, Richard Anuszkiewicz, Bridget Riley and others.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The exhibition focused on the perceptual aspects of art, which result both from the illusion of movement and the interaction of color relationships.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art, also known as optical art, is a style present in some paintings and other works of art that use optical illusions.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is also closely akin to geometric abstraction and hard-edge painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although sometimes the term used for it is perceptual abstraction.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is a method of painting concerning the interaction between illusion and picture plane, between understanding and seeing.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art works are abstract, with many of the better known pieces made in only black and white.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] When the viewer looks at them, the impression is given of movement, hidden images, flashing and vibration, patterns, or alternatively, of swelling or warping.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting clearly pointed toward a new direction in American painting, away from abstract expressionism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting is related to Post-painterly abstraction, Suprematism, Abstract Expressionism, Hard-edge painting and Lyrical Abstraction.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting sought to rid art of superfluous rhetoric.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Certain artists made references to past or present art, but in general color field painting presents abstraction as an end in itself.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In pursuing this direction of modern art, artists wanted to present each painting as one unified, cohesive, monolithic image.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Frank Stella, Kenneth Noland, Ellsworth Kelly, Barnett Newman, Ronald Davis, Neil Williams, Robert Mangold, Charles Hinman, Richard Tuttle, David Novros, and Alvin Loving are examples of artists associated with the use of the shaped canvas during the period beginning in the early 1960s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] From 1960 Frank Stella produced paintings in aluminium and copper paint and are his first works using shaped canvases (canvases in a shape other than the traditional rectangle or square), often being in L, N, U or T-shapes.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These later developed into more elaborate designs, in the *Irregular Polygon* series (67), for example.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Also in the 1960s, Stella began to use a wider range of colors, typically arranged in straight or curved lines.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later he began his *Protractor Series* (71) of paintings, in which arcs, sometimes overlapping, within square borders are arranged side-by-side to produce full and half circles painted in rings of concentric color.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Harran II,* 1967, is an example of the *Protractor Series*.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These paintings are named after circular cities he had visited while in the Middle East earlier in the 1960s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Irregular Polygon canvases and Protractor series further extended the concept of the shaped canvas.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Andre Emmerich Gallery, the Leo Castelli Gallery, the Richard Feigen Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Color Field painting, shaped canvas painting and Lyrical Abstraction in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s Color Field painting and Minimal art were often closely associated with each other.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In actuality by the early 1970s both movements became decidedly diverse.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Another related movement of the late 1960s, Lyrical Abstraction (the term being coined by Larry Aldrich, the founder of the Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum, Ridgefield Connecticut), encompassed what Aldrich said he saw in the studios of many artists at that time.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It is also the name of an exhibition that originated in the Aldrich Museum and traveled to the Whitney Museum of American Art and other museums throughout the United States between 1969 and 1971.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Postminimalism often incorporating industrial materials, raw materials, fabrications, found objects, installation, serial repetition, and often with references to Dada and Surrealism is best exemplified in the sculptures of Eva Hesse.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction is a type of freewheeling abstract painting that emerged in the mid-1960s when abstract painters returned to various forms of painterly, pictorial, expressionism with a predominate focus on process, gestalt and repetitive compositional strategies in general.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction shares similarities with Color Field painting and Abstract Expressionism especially in the freewheeling usage of paint – texture and surface.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Direct drawing, calligraphic use of line, the effects of brushed, splattered, stained, squeegeed, poured, and splashed paint superficially resemble the effects seen in Abstract Expressionism and Color Field painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] However the styles are markedly different.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Setting it apart from Abstract Expressionism and Action Painting of the 1940s and 1950s is the approach to composition and drama.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] As seen in Action Painting there is an emphasis on brushstrokes, high compositional drama, dynamic compositional tension.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in Lyrical Abstraction as exemplified by the 1971 Ronnie Landfield painting *Garden of Delight* (above), there is a sense of compositional randomness, all over composition, low key and relaxed compositional drama and an emphasis on process, repetition, and an all over sensibility.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Donald Judd had started as a painter, and ended as a creator of objects.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His seminal essay, "Specific Objects" (published in Arts Yearbook 8, 1965), was a touchstone of theory for the formation of Minimalist aesthetics.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this essay, Judd found a starting point for a new territory for American art, and a simultaneous rejection of residual inherited European artistic values.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He pointed to evidence of this development in the works of an array of artists active in New York at the time, including Jasper Johns, Dan Flavin and Lee Bontecou.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Of "preliminary" importance for Judd was the work of George Earl Ortman, who had concretized and distilled painting's forms into blunt, tough, philosophically charged geometries.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These Specific Objects inhabited a space not then comfortably classifiable as either painting or sculpture.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] That the categorical identity of such objects was itself in question, and that they avoided easy association with well-worn and over-familiar conventions, was a part of their value for Judd.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] American painters such as Brice Marden and Cy Twombly show a clear European influence in their *pure* abstraction, minimalist painting of the 1960s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ronald Davis polyurethane works from the late 1960s pay homage to the *Broken Glass* of Marcel Duchamp.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement was heavily criticised by high modernist formalist art critics and historians.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some anxious critics thought Minimalist art represented a misunderstanding of the modern dialectic of painting and sculpture as defined by critic Clement Greenberg, arguably the dominant American critic of painting in the period leading up to the 1960s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The most notable critique of Minimalism was produced by Michael Fried, a Greenbergian critic, who objected to the work on the basis of its "theatricality".
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In *Art and Objecthood* (published in Artforum in June 1967) he declared that the Minimalist work of art, particularly Minimalist sculpture, was based on an engagement with the physicality of the spectator.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He argued that work like Robert Morris's transformed the act of viewing into a type of spectacle, in which the artifice of the act observation and the viewer's participation in the work were unveiled.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fried saw this displacement of the viewer's experience from an aesthetic engagement within, to an event outside of the artwork as a failure of Minimal art.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ad Reinhardt, actually an artist of the Abstract Expressionist generation, but one whose reductive all-black paintings seemed to anticipate minimalism, had this to say about the value of a reductive approach to art: "The more stuff in it, the busier the work of art, the worse it is.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Still other important innovations in abstract painting took place during the 1960s and the 1970s characterized by monochrome painting and hard-edge painting inspired by Ad Reinhardt, Barnett Newman, Milton Resnick, and Ellsworth Kelly.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Artists as diverse as Agnes Martin, Al Held, Larry Zox, Frank Stella, Larry Poons, Brice Marden and others explored the power of simplification.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The convergence of Color Field painting, minimal art, hard-edge painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and postminimalism blurred the distinction between movements that became more apparent in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The neo-expressionism movement is related to earlier developments in abstract expressionism, neo-Dada, Lyrical Abstraction and postminimal painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works were inspirational to a new generation of painters interested in a revival of expressive imagery.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His painting *Painting, Smoking, Eating* 1973, seen above in the gallery is an example of Guston's final and conclusive return to representation.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, there was also a return to painting that occurred almost simultaneously in Italy, Germany, France and Britain.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These movements were called Transavantguardia, Neue Wilde, Figuration Libre, Neo-expressionism, the school of London, and in the late 1990s the Stuckists, a group that emerged late in 1990s respectively.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These painting were characterized by large formats, free expressive mark making, figuration, myth and imagination.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] All work in this genre came to be labeled neo-expressionism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some critics regarded it as driven by profit motivations by large commercial galleries.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This type of art continues in popularity into the 21st century, even after the art crash of the late 1980s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the late 1970s in the United States painters who began working with invigorated surfaces and who returned to imagery like Susan Rothenberg gained in popularity, especially as seen above in paintings like *Horse 2,* 1979.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1980s American artists like Eric Fischl, David Salle, Jean-Michel Basquiat (who began as a graffiti artist), Julian Schnabel, and Keith Haring, and Italian painters like Mimmo Paladino, Sandro Chia, and Enzo Cucchi, among others defined the idea of Neo-expressionism in America.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionism was a style of modern painting that became popular in the late 1970s and dominated the art market until the mid-1980s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It developed in Europe as a reaction against the conceptual and minimalistic art of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionists returned to portraying recognizable objects, such as the human body (although sometimes in a virtually abstract manner), in a rough and violently emotional way using vivid colours and banal colour harmonies.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The veteran painters Philip Guston, Frank Auerbach, Leon Kossoff, Gerhard Richter, A.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Penck and Georg Baselitz, along with slightly younger artists like Anselm Kiefer, Eric Fischl, Susan Rothenberg, Francesco Clemente, Damien Hirst, Jean-Michel Basquiat, Julian Schnabel, Keith Haring, and many others became known for working in this intense expressionist vein of painting.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] At the beginning of the 21st century Contemporary painting and Contemporary art in general continues in several contiguous modes, characterized by the idea of pluralism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Mainstream painting has been rejected by artists of the postmodern era in favor of artistic pluralism.
[src:early-modern-period/20th-century-western-painting-p02] According to art critic Arthur Danto there is an *anything goes* attitude that prevails; an "everything going on", and consequently "nothing going on" syndrome; this creates an aesthetic traffic jam with no firm and clear direction and with every lane on the artistic superhighway filled to capacity.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] 1800, is a historical period, with divisions based primarily on the history of Europe and the broader concept of modernity.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] There is no exact date that marks the beginning or end of the period and its extent may vary depending on the area of history being studied.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In general, the early modern period is considered to have started at the beginning of the 16th or 17th century (c.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] 1600), and is variably considered to have ended at the 18th or 19th century (1700–1800).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In a European context, it is defined as the period following the Middle Ages and preceding the advent of modernity, but there is no universal agreement on the dates of these boundaries.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the context of global history, the early modern period is often used in contexts where there is no equivalent "medieval" period.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Various events and historical transitions have been proposed as the start of the early modern period, including the start of the Renaissance, the beginning of the printing revolution in the 1440s, the Fall of Constantinople in 1453, the Age of Discovery or the start of the Reformation.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Its end is often marked by the French Revolution, and sometimes also the American Revolution or Napoleon's rise to power, with the advent of the second wave of modern colonization known as New Imperialism.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Historians in recent decades have argued that, from a worldwide standpoint, the most important feature of the early modern period was the spread of globalization.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] From this viewpoint, the Columbian contact and its newfound notion of a New World being added to the Old World is another marker of the start of the period.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] New economies and institutions emerged, becoming more sophisticated and globally articulated over the course of the period.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The early modern period also included the rise of the dominance of mercantilism as an economic theory.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Other notable developments of the period include the Scientific Revolution, increasingly rapid technological progress, secularized civic politics, accelerated travel due to improvements in mapping and ship design, and the emergence of nation states.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The concept of the early modern period originated in the study of European history, which since the time of Petrarch and other Renaissance humanists has traditionally been divided into three periods: ancient, medieval, and modern.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The term *early modern* was occasionally used by historians in the early 20th century (the first known usage dates to 1895), but the vast majority of these instances use the term merely to refer to the early centuries of the modern period, not to denote a distinct period with defining features.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The term *early modern* was first proposed to denote a distinct period of European history by medieval historian Lynn Thorndike.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In his 1926 work *A Short History of Civilization*, Thorndike proposed the periodization as a broader alternative to the Renaissance.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] It was first picked up within the field of economic history during the 1940s and 1950s and gradually spread to other historians in the following decades and became widely known among scholars during the 1990s.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] It was more popular among historians in North American than in Europe, where, according to Jerry H.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Bentley, "Strong traditions of national historiography discouraged […] scholars from efforts to explore a larger European past".
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The first attempts to apply the periodization beyond Europe in a substantive manner came by the 1980s.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Some scholars used the term while studying Asian societies (such as Tokugawa Japan) that underwent developments similar or comparable to those in early modern Europe.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Others argued that early modern Eurasia was distinguished by interconnections and common experiences, including territorial consolidation, demographic growth, inflation, and social mobility, among others.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Fletcher also suggested the possibility of the periodization's applicability on a global scale.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Another group of scholars has made the case for the early modern period as a recognizable era of world history, citing various processes that affected the entire world.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] He identifies the connection of the world by sea, global biological exchanges, and the creation of an "early capitalist global economy" as the three main processes that spurred the creation of the early modern world and led to other major developments that affected people around the world.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] At the onset of the early modern period, trends in various regions of the world represented a shift away from medieval modes of organization, politically and economically.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Feudalism declined in Europe, and Christendom saw the end of the Crusades and of religious unity in Western Europe under the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Along with the European colonization of the Americas, this period also contained the Commercial Revolution, the Scientific Revolution and the Golden Age of Piracy.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The globalization of the period can be seen in the medieval North Italian city-states and maritime republics, particularly Genoa, Venice, and Milan.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Russia reached the Pacific coast in 1647 and consolidated its control over the Russian Far East in the 19th century.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Great Divergence took place as Western Europe greatly surpassed China in technology and per capita wealth.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] As the Age of Revolution dawned, beginning with revolts in America and France, political changes were then pushed forward in other countries.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] This was partly as a result of the upheavals of the Napoleonic Wars and their impact on the world of ideas and thought of the time: concepts from nationalism to organizing armies were attracting attention and debate.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the Americas, pre-Columbian peoples had built a large and varied civilization, including the Aztec Empire, the Inca civilization, the Maya civilization and its cities, and the Muisca.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The European colonization of the Americas began during the early modern period, as did the establishment of European trading hubs in Asia and Africa, which contributed to the spread of Christianity around the world.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The rise of sustained contacts between previously isolated parts of the globe, in particular the Columbian Exchange that linked the Old World and the New World, greatly altered the human environment.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Notably, the Atlantic slave trade and colonization of Indigenous peoples of the Americas began during this period.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Ottoman Empire conquered Southeastern Europe, and parts of West Asia and North Africa.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the Islamic world, after the fall of the Timurid Renaissance, powers such as the Ottoman, Suri, Safavid, and Mughal empires grew in strength (three of which are known as gunpowder empires for the military technology that enabled them).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Particularly in the Indian subcontinent, Mughal architecture, culture, and art reached their zenith, while the empire itself is believed to have had the world's largest economy, bigger than the entirety of Western Europe and worth 25% of global GDP.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] By the mid-18th century, India was a major proto-industrializing region.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Various Chinese dynasties controlled the East Asian sphere.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In Japan, the Edo period from 1600 to 1868 is also referred to as the early modern period.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In Korea, the early modern period is considered to have lasted from the rise of the Joseon dynasty to the enthronement of King Gojong.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] By the 16th century, Asian economies under the Ming dynasty and Mughal Bengal were stimulated by trade with the Portuguese, the Spanish, and the Dutch, while Japan engaged in the Nanban trade after the arrival of the first European Portuguese during the Azuchi–Momoyama period.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The early modern period experienced an influx of European traders and missionaries into the region.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In early modern times, the major nations of East Asia attempted to pursue a course of isolationism from the outside world but this policy was not always enforced uniformly or successfully.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] However, by the end of the early modern period, China, Korea and Japan were mostly closed and uninterested in Europeans, even while trading relationships grew in port cities such as Guangzhou and Dejima.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Around the beginning of the ethnically Han Ming dynasty (1368–1644), China was leading the world in mathematics as well as science.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] However, Europe soon caught up to China's scientific and mathematical achievements and surpassed them.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Many scholars have speculated about the reason behind China's lag in advancement.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] A historian named Colin Ronan claims that though there is no one specific answer, there must be a connection between China's urgency for new discoveries being weaker than Europe's and China's inability to capitalize on its early advantages.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Ronan believes that China's Confucian bureaucracy and traditions led to China not having a scientific revolution, which led China to have fewer scientists to break the existing orthodoxies, like Galileo Galilei.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Despite inventing gunpowder in the 9th century, it was in Europe that the classic handheld firearms, matchlocks, were invented, with evidence of use around the 1480s.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] China was using the matchlocks by 1540, after the Portuguese brought their matchlocks to Japan in the early 1500s.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] China during the Ming dynasty established a bureau to maintain its calendar.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The bureau was necessary because the calendars were linked to celestial phenomena and that needs regular maintenance because twelve lunar months have 344 or 355 days, so occasional leap months have to be added in order to maintain 365 days per year.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the early Ming dynasty, urbanization increased as the population grew and as the division of labor grew more complex.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Large urban centers, such as Nanjing and Beijing, also contributed to the growth of private industry.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In particular, small-scale industries grew up, often specializing in paper, silk, cotton, and porcelain goods.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] For the most part, however, relatively small urban centers with markets proliferated around the country.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Town markets mainly traded food, with some necessary manufactures such as pins or oil.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the 16th century the Ming dynasty flourished over maritime trade with the Portuguese, Spanish and Dutch Empires.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The trade brought in a massive amount of silver, which China at the time needed desperately.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Prior to China's global trade, its economy ran on paper money.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] However, in the 14th century, China's paper money system suffered a crisis, and by the mid-15th century, crashed.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The silver imports helped fill the void left by the broken paper money system, which helps explain why the value of silver in China was twice as high as the value of silver in Spain during the end of the 16th century.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] China under the later Ming dynasty became isolated, prohibiting the construction of ocean going sea vessels.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Despite isolationist policies the Ming economy still suffered from an inflation due to an overabundance of Spanish New World silver entering its economy through new European colonies such as Macau.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Ming China was further strained by victorious but costly wars to protect Korea from Japanese invasion.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The damage to the economy was compounded by the effects on agriculture of the incipient Little Ice Age, natural calamities, crop failure and sudden epidemics.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The ensuing breakdown of authority and people's livelihoods allowed rebel leaders, such as Li Zicheng, to challenge Ming authority.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Ming dynasty fell around 1644 to the ethnically Manchu Qing dynasty, which would be the last dynasty of China.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Qing ruled from 1644 to 1912, with a brief, abortive restoration in 1917.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] During its reign, the Qing dynasty adopted many of the outward features of Chinese culture in establishing its rule, but did not necessarily "assimilate", instead adopting a more universalist style of governance.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Manchus were formerly known as the Jurchens.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] When Beijing was captured by Li Zicheng's peasant rebels in 1644, the Chongzhen Emperor, the last Ming emperor, committed suicide.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Manchus then allied with former Ming general Wu Sangui and seized control of Beijing, which became the new capital of the Qing dynasty.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Manchus adopted the Confucian norms of traditional Chinese government in their rule of China proper.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Sengoku period that began around 1467 and lasted around a century consisted of several continually "warring states".
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Central government was largely reestablished by Oda Nobunaga and Toyotomi Hideyoshi during the Azuchi–Momoyama period.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Tokugawa received the title of *shōgun* in 1603, establishing the Tokugawa shogunate.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Edo period from 1600 to 1868 characterized early modern Japan.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Tokugawa shogunate was a feudalist regime of Japan established by Tokugawa Ieyasu and ruled by the *shōguns* of the Tokugawa clan.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The period gets its name from the capital city, Edo, now called Tokyo.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Tokugawa shogunate ruled from Edo Castle from 1603 until 1868, when it was abolished during the Meiji Restoration in the late Edo period (often called the Late Tokugawa shogunate).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Society in the Japanese "Tokugawa period" (Edo society), unlike the shogunates before it, was based on the strict class hierarchy originally established by Toyotomi Hideyoshi.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The *daimyōs* (feudal lords) were at the top, followed by the warrior-caste of samurai, with the farmers, artisans, and traders ranking below.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The country was strictly closed to foreigners with few exceptions with the *Sakoku* policy.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Literacy among the Japanese people rose in the two centuries of isolation.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In some parts of the country, particularly smaller regions, *daimyōs* and samurai were more or less identical, since *daimyōs* might be trained as samurai, and samurai might act as local lords.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Otherwise, the largely inflexible nature of this social stratification system unleashed disruptive forces over time.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Taxes on the peasantry were set at fixed amounts which did not account for inflation or other changes in monetary value.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] As a result, the tax revenues collected by the samurai landowners were worth less and less over time.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] This often led to numerous confrontations between noble but impoverished samurai and well-to-do peasants.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] None, however, proved compelling enough to seriously challenge the established order until the arrival of foreign powers.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In 1392, General Yi Seong-gye established the Joseon dynasty (1392–1910) with a largely bloodless coup.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Yi Seong-gye moved the capital of Korea to the location of modern-day Seoul.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The dynasty was heavily influenced by Confucianism, which also played a large role to shaping Korea's strong cultural identity.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] King Sejong the Great (1418–1450), one of the only two kings in Korea's history to earn the title of great in their posthumous titles, reclaimed Korean territory to the north and created the Korean alphabet.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] During the end of the 16th century, Korea was invaded twice by Japan, first in 1592 and again in 1597.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Japan failed both times due to Admiral Yi Sun-sin, Korea's revered naval genius, who led the Korean Navy using advanced metal clad ships called turtle ships.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Because the ships were armed with cannons, Admiral Yi's navy was able to demolish the Japanese invading fleets, destroying hundreds of ships in Japan's second invasion.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] During the 17th century, Korea was invaded again, this time by Manchurians, who would later take over China as the Qing dynasty.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In 1637, King Injo was forced to surrender to the Qing forces, and was ordered to send princesses as concubines to the Qing Prince Dorgon.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The rise of the Mughal Empire is usually dated from 1526, around the end of the Middle Ages.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] It was an Islamic Persianate imperial power that ruled most of the area as Hindustan by the late 17th and the early 18th centuries.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The empire dominated South Asia, becoming the largest global economy and manufacturing power, with a nominal GDP valued at a quarter of the global economy, superior than the combined GDP of Europe.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The empire, prior to the death of the last prominent emperor Aurangzeb, was marked by a highly centralized administration connecting its different provinces.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] All the significant monuments of the Mughals, their most visible legacy, date to this period which was characterized by the expansion of Persian cultural influence in the Indian subcontinent, with brilliant literary, artistic, and architectural results.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Maratha Confederacy, founded in the southwest of present-day India, surpassed the Mughals as the dominant power in India from 1740 and rapidly expanded until the Third Battle of Panipat halted their expansion in 1761.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The development of New Imperialism saw the conquest of nearly all eastern hemisphere territories by colonial powers.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Maratha Confederacy, following the Anglo-Maratha wars, eventually lost to the British East India Company in 1818 with the Third Anglo-Maratha War.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Rule by the Company lasted until 1858, when, after the Indian rebellion of 1857 and following the Government of India Act 1858, the British government assumed the task of directly administering India in the new British Raj.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In 1819, Stamford Raffles established Singapore as a key trading post for Britain in its rivalry with the Dutch.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] However, the rivalry cooled in 1824 when an Anglo-Dutch treaty demarcated their respective interests in Southeast Asia.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] From the 1850s onwards, the pace of colonization shifted to a significantly higher gear.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] At the start of the modern era, the Spice Route between India and China crossed Majapahit, an archipelagic empire based on the island of Java.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] It was the last of the major Hindu empires of Maritime Southeast Asia and is considered one of the greatest states in Indonesian history.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Its influence extended to Sumatra, the Malay Peninsula, Borneo, and eastern Indonesia, though the effectiveness of this influence remains debated.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Majapahit struggled to control the rising Sultanate of Malacca, which dominated Muslim Malay settlements in Phuket, Satun, Pattani, and Sumatra.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Portuguese invaded Malacca's capital in 1511, and by 1528, the Sultanate of Johor was established by a Malaccan prince to succeed Malacca.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] While in Borneo, Brunei began their golden age during the reign of Sultan Bolkiah when he defeated the Kingdom of Tondo in the Tondo War however but was paused when it fought the Spanish in the Castilian War in 1578.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] During the early modern era, the Ottoman Empire enjoyed an expansion and consolidation of power, leading to a *Pax Ottomana*.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] This was perhaps the golden age of the empire.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Ottomans expanded southwest into North Africa while battling with the re-emergent Persian Shi'a Safavid Empire to the east.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the Ottoman sphere, the Turks seized Egypt in 1517 and established the regencies of Algeria, Tunisia, and Tripolitania (between 1519 and 1551), Morocco remaining an independent Arabized Berber state under the Sharifan dynasty.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Safavid Empire was a great Shia Persianate empire after the Islamic conquest of Persia and the establishment of Islam, marking an important point in the history of Islam in the east.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Safavid dynasty was founded about 1501.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] From their base in Ardabil, the Safavids established control over all of Persia and reasserted the Iranian identity of the region, thus becoming the first native dynasty since the Sassanids to establish a unified Iranian state.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Problematic for the Safavids was the powerful Ottoman Empire.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Ottomans, a Sunni dynasty, fought several campaigns against the Safavids.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] What fueled the growth of Safavid economy was its position between the burgeoning civilizations of Europe to its west and Islamic Central Asia to its east and north.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Silk Road, which led from Europe to East Asia, revived in the 16th century.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Leaders also supported direct sea trade with Europe, particularly England and The Netherlands, which sought Persian carpet, silk, and textiles.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Other exports were horses, goat hair, pearls, and an inedible bitter almond hadam-talka used as a spice in India.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The main imports were spice, textiles (woolens from Europe, cotton from Gujarat), metals, coffee, and sugar.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Despite their demise in 1722, the Safavids left their mark by establishing and spreading Shi'a Islam in major parts of the Caucasus and West Asia.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the 16th to early 18th centuries, Central Asia was under the rule of Uzbeks, and the far eastern portions were ruled by the local Pashtuns.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Between the 15th and 16th centuries, various nomadic tribes arrived from the steppes, including the Kipchaks, Naimans, Kangly, Khongirad, and Manghuds.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] These groups were led by Muhammad Shaybani, who was the Khan of the Uzbeks.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The lineage of the Afghan Pashtuns stretches back to the Hotaki dynasty.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Following Muslim Arab and Turkic conquests, Pashtun *ghazis* (warriors for the faith) invaded and conquered much of northern India during the Lodhi dynasty and Suri dynasty.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Pashtun forces also invaded Persia, and the opposing forces were defeated in the Battle of Gulnabad.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Pashtuns later formed the Durrani Empire.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Songhai Empire took control of the trans-Saharan trade at the beginning of the modern era.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] It seized Timbuktu in 1468 and Jenne in 1473, building the regime on trade revenues and the cooperation of Muslim merchants.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The empire eventually made Islam the official religion, built mosques, and brought Muslim scholars to Gao.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Many major events caused Europe to change around the start of the 16th century, starting with the Fall of Constantinople in 1453, the fall of Muslim Spain and the discovery of the Americas in 1492, and Martin Luther's Protestant Reformation in 1517.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In England the modern period is often dated to the start of the Tudor period with the victory of Henry VII over Richard III at the Battle of Bosworth in 1485.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Early modern European history is usually seen to span from the start of the 15th century, through the Age of Enlightenment in the 17th and 18th centuries, until the beginning of the Industrial Revolution in the late 18th century.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The early modern period is taken to end with the French Revolution, the Napoleonic Wars, and the Dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire at the Congress of Vienna.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] When gunpowder was introduced to Europe, it was immediately used almost exclusively in weapons and explosives for warfare.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Though it was invented in China, gunpowder arrived in Europe already formulated for military use; European countries took advantage of this and were the first to create the classic firearms.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The advances made in gunpowder and firearms was directly tied to the decline in the use of plate armor because of the inability of the armor to protect one from bullets.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The musket was able to penetrate all forms of armor available at the time, making armor obsolete, and as a consequence the heavy musket as well.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Although there is relatively little to no difference in design between arquebus and musket except in size and strength, it was the term *musket* which remained in use up into the 1800s.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the early modern period, the Holy Roman Empire was a union of territories in Central Europe under a Holy Roman Emperor the first of which was Otto I.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The last was Francis II, who abdicated and dissolved the Empire in 1806 during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Despite its name, for much of its history the Empire did not include Rome within its borders.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Renaissance was a cultural movement that began in the 14th century, beginning in Italy in the Late Middle Ages and later spreading to the rest of Europe.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The term is also used more loosely to refer to the historic era, but since the changes of the Renaissance were not uniform across Europe, this is a general use of the term.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] As a cultural movement, it encompassed a rebellion of learning based on classical sources, the development of linear perspective in painting, and gradual but widespread educational reform.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Johannes Gutenberg is credited as the first European to use movable type printing, around 1439, and as the global inventor of the mechanical printing press.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Nicolaus Copernicus formulated a comprehensive heliocentric cosmology (1543), which displaced the Earth from the center of the universe.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] His book, *De revolutionibus orbium coelestium* (*On the Revolutions of the Celestial Spheres*) began modern astronomy and sparked the Scientific Revolution.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Another notable individual was Machiavelli, an Italian political philosopher, considered a founder of modern political science.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Machiavelli is most famous for a short political treatise, *The Prince*, a work of realist political theory.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Swiss Paracelsus (1493–1541) is associated with a medical revolution while the Anglo-Irish Robert Boyle was one of the founders of modern chemistry.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Famous composers included Guillaume Du Fay, Heinrich Isaac, Josquin des Prez, Giovanni Pierluigi da Palestrina, Claudio Monteverdi, Jean-Baptiste Lully.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Among the notable royalty of the time was Charles the Bold (1433–1477), the last Valois Duke of Burgundy, known as *Charles the Bold (or Rash)* to his enemies, His early death was a pivotal moment in European history.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Charles has often been regarded as the last representative of the feudal spirit, although in administrative affairs, he introduced remarkable modernizing innovations.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Upon his death, Charles left an unmarried nineteen-year-old daughter, Mary of Burgundy, as his heir.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Her marriage would have enormous implications for the political balance of Europe.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Frederick III, Holy Roman Emperor secured the match for his son, the future Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor, with the aid of Mary's stepmother, Margaret.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In 1477, the territory of the Duchy of Burgundy was annexed by France.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the same year, Mary married Maximilian, Archduke of Austria.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] A conflict between the Burgundian side (Maximilian brought with himself almost no resources from the Empire) and France ensued, culminating in the Treaty of Senlis (1493) which gave the majority of Burgundian inheritance to the Habsburg (Mary already died in 1482).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The rise of the Habsburg dynasty was a prime factor in the spreading of the Renaissance.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In Central Europe, King Matthias Corvinus (1443–1490), a notable nation builder, conqueror (Hungary in his time was the most powerful in Central Europe) and patron, was the first who introduced the Renaissance outside of Italy.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In military area, he introduced the Black Army, one of the first standing armies in Europe and a remarkably modern force.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Some noblemen from the generation that lived during this period have been attributed the moniker "the last knight", with the most notable being the above-mentioned Maximilian I (1459–1519), Chevalier de Bayard (1476–1524), Franz von Sickingen (1481–1523) and Götz von Berlichingen (1480–1562).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Christianity was challenged at the beginning of the modern period with the fall of Constantinople in 1453 and later by various movements to reform the church (including Lutheran, Zwinglian, and Calvinist), followed by the Counter Reformation.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Hussite Crusades (1419–1434) involved military actions against the followers of Jan Hus in Bohemia, concluding with the Battle of Grotniki.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] These wars were notable for being among the first European conflicts where hand-held gunpowder weapons, like muskets, played a decisive role.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Taborite faction of Hussite warriors, primarily infantry, decisively defeated larger armies with heavily armored knights, contributing to the infantry revolution.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] However, the Hussite Crusades were ultimately inconclusive.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The final crusade, the Crusade of 1456, was organized to counter the advancing Ottoman Empire and lift the Siege of Belgrade (1456), led by John Hunyadi and Giovanni da Capistrano.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The siege culminated in a counterattack that forced Sultan Mehmet II to retreat, with the victory being credited with deciding the fate of Christendom.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The noon bell, ordered by Pope Callixtus III, commemorates this victory across the Christian world to this day.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Nearly a century later, the Peace of Augsburg (1555) ended the concept of a united Christian church.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The principle of *cuius regio, eius religio* allowed rulers to determine their state's religion.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] This framework was solidified by the Treaty of Westphalia (1648), which ended the European Wars of Religion and the notion of a singular Christian hegemony.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The treaty also marked the birth of the modern concept of national sovereignty.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Inquisition in the modern era refers to several institutions within the Catholic Church tasked with prosecuting heretics and others who violated canon law.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The first significant manifestation was the Spanish Inquisition (1478–1834).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Inquisition prosecuted crimes such as sorcery, blasphemy, Judaizing, witchcraft, and censorship of printed literature.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Its jurisdiction was limited to baptized Catholics, while non-Christians were typically tried by secular courts.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Reformation and rise of modernity in the early 16th century brought changes to Christendom.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Augustinian friar Martin Luther in Germany challenged the Church with his Ninety-five Theses, marking the start of the Reformation.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Luther's movement, supported by the Electorate of Saxony, developed at the University of Wittenberg, where he became a professor.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Luther's 95 Theses criticized practices like the sale of indulgences and sparked debates, leading to the rise of rival Protestant denominations, such as Lutheranism and the Reformed tradition.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In England, the movement became known as the English Reformation, resulting in the formation of Anglicanism.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Diet of Worms (1521) declared Luther a heretic, but Emperor Charles V was preoccupied with external threats and allowed German princes to decide whether to enforce the Edict of Worms.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The religious conflict escalated, leading to the formation of the Schmalkaldic League to defend Protestant interests.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] This culminated in the Peace of Augsburg (1555), which established the principle of cuius regio, eius religio—allowing rulers to determine the religion of their territories.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Counter-Reformation began in 1545 with the Council of Trent in response to the Protestant Reformation.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Its goal was to reform internal Church practices while reaffirming the Church's authority as the true Church of Christ.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In development of the Third Rome ideas, the Grand Duke Ivan IV (the "Awesome" or "the Terrible") was officially crowned the first Tsar ("Caesar") of Russia in 1547.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Tsar promulgated a new code of laws (Sudebnik of 1550), established the first Russian feudal representative body (Zemsky Sobor) and introduced local self-management into the rural regions.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] During his long reign, Ivan IV nearly doubled the already large Russian territory by annexing the three Tatar khanates (parts of disintegrated Golden Horde): Kazan and Astrakhan along the Volga River, and Sibirean Khanate in South Western Siberia.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Thus by the end of the 16th century Russia was transformed into a multiethnic, multiconfessional and transcontinental state.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Russia experienced territorial growth through the 17th century, which was the age of Cossacks.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Cossacks were warriors organized into military communities, resembling pirates and pioneers of the New World.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The native land of the Cossacks is defined by a line of Russian/Ruthenian town-fortresses located on the border with the steppe and stretching from the middle Volga to Ryazan and Tula, then breaking abruptly to the south and extending to the Dnieper via Pereyaslavl.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] This area was settled by a population of free people practicing various trades and crafts.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] In the Old World, the most desired trading goods were gold, silver, and spices.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Western Europeans used the compass, new sailing ship technologies, new maps, and advances in astronomy to seek a viable trade route to Asia for valuable spices that Mediterranean powers could not contest.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Golden Age of Piracy is a designation given to one or more outbursts of piracy in the early modern period, spanning from the mid-17th century to the mid-18th century.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The buccaneering period covers approximately the late 17th century.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] This period was characterized by Anglo-French seamen based in Jamaica and Tortuga attacking Spanish colonies and shipping in the Caribbean and eastern Pacific.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Pirate Round was a route followed by certain Anglo-American pirates in the early 18th century, involving voyages from Bermuda and the Americas to attack Muslim and East India Company ships in the Indian Ocean and Red Sea.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The post-War of the Spanish Succession period saw many unemployed sailors and privateers turning to piracy in the Caribbean, the American eastern seaboard, West Africa, and the Indian Ocean.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The 15th to 18th century period is marked by the first European colonies, the rise of strong centralized governments, and the beginnings of recognizable European nation states that are the direct antecedents of today's states.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Although the Renaissance included revolutions in many intellectual pursuits, as well as social and political upheaval, it is perhaps best known for European artistic developments and the contributions of such polymaths as Leonardo da Vinci and Michelangelo, who inspired the term "Renaissance man".
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Peace of Westphalia resulted from the first modern diplomatic congress.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Until 1806, the regulations became part of the constitutional laws of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Treaty of the Pyrenees, signed in 1659, ended the war between France and Spain and is often considered part of the overall accord.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Men who featured prominently in the political and military life of France during this period include Mazarin, Colbert, Turenne, Vauban.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] French culture likewise flourished during this era, producing a number of figures of great renown, including Molière, Racine, Boileau, La Fontaine, Lully, Le Brun, Rigaud, Louis Le Vau, Jules Hardouin Mansart, Claude Perrault and Le Nôtre.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Before the Age of Revolution, the English Civil War was a series of armed conflicts and political machinations between Parliamentarians and Royalists.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The first and second civil wars pitted the supporters of King Charles I against the supporters of the Long Parliament, while the third war saw fighting between supporters of King Charles II and supporters of the Rump Parliament.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Civil War ended with the Parliamentary victory at the Battle of Worcester.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The monopoly of the Church of England on Christian worship in England ended with the victors consolidating the established Protestant Ascendancy in Ireland.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Constitutionally, the wars established the precedent that an English monarch cannot govern without Parliament's consent.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The English Restoration, or simply put as the Restoration, began in 1660 when the English, Scottish and Irish monarchies were all restored under Charles II after the Commonwealth of England that followed the English Civil War.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Glorious Revolution of 1688 establishes modern parliamentary democracy in England.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Peace of Utrecht established after a series of individual peace treaties signed in the Dutch city of Utrecht concluded between various European states helped end the War of the Spanish Succession.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The representatives who met were Louis XIV of France and Philip V of Spain on the one hand, and representatives of Queen Anne of Great Britain, the Duke of Savoy, and the United Provinces on the other.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The treaty enregistered the defeat of French ambitions expressed in the wars of Louis XIV and preserved the European system based on the balance of power.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Treaty of Utrecht marked the change from Dutch to British naval supremacy.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The term *colonialism* is normally used with reference to discontiguous overseas empires rather than contiguous land-based empires, European or otherwise.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] European colonisation during the 15th to 19th centuries resulted in the spread of Christianity to Sub-Saharan Africa, the Americas, Australia and the Philippines.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Initially, Portuguese settlements (Brazil) in the coastal northeast were of lesser importance in the larger Portuguese overseas empire, where lucrative commerce and small settlements devoted to trade were established in coastal Africa, India and China.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] With sparse indigenous populations that could not be coerced to work and no known deposits of precious metals, Portugal sought a high-value, low-bulk export product and found it in sugarcane.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Black African slave labour from Portugal's West African possessions was imported to do the grueling agricultural work.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] As the wealth of the Ibero-America increased, some Western European powers (Dutch, French, British, Danish) sought to duplicate the model in areas that the Iberians had not settled in numbers.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] They seized some Caribbean islands from the Spanish and transferred the model of sugar production on plantations with slave labour and settled in northern areas of North America in what are now the Eastern Seaboard of the United States and Canada.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] North America outside the zone of Spanish settlement was a contested area in the 17th century.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] Spain had founded small settlements in Florida and Georgia, but nowhere near the size of those in New Spain or the Caribbean islands.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] France, The Netherlands, and Great Britain held colonies in North America and the West Indies from the 17th century, 100 years after the Spanish and Portuguese established permanent colonies.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The British colonies in North America were founded between 1607 (Virginia) and 1733 (Georgia).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Dutch explored the east coast of North America and began founding settlements in what they called New Netherland (now New York State.).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] France colonized what is now Eastern Canada, founding Quebec City in 1608.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] France's loss in the Seven Years' War resulted in the transfer of New France to Great Britain.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The Thirteen Colonies, in lower British North America, rebelled against British rule through 1765–1783, due to various factors such as belief in natural rights, the enforcement of new taxes levied by a Parliament which they could not vote for representatives in, and opposition to monarchy.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The British colonies in Canada remained loyal to the crown, and a provisional government formed by the Thirteen Colonies proclaimed their independence on 4 July 1776, and subsequently became the original 13 United States of America.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] With the 1783 Treaty of Paris ending the American Revolutionary War, Britain recognised the former Thirteen Colonies' independence.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] A key development in early modern history is the creation of the Atlantic World as a category.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] The term generally encompasses Western Europe, West Africa, and the Americas.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p01] It seeks to illustrate both local and regional developments, as well as the connections between these geographical regions through trade, migration, and cultural exchange.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The early modern period was initiated by the Reformation and the collapse of the unity of the medieval Western Church.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The theology of Calvinism in particular has been argued as instrumental to the rise of capitalism.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The Counter-Reformation was a period of Catholic revival in response to the Reformation during the mid-16th to mid-17th centuries.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The Counter-Reformation was a comprehensive effort, involving ecclesiastical reforms as well as political and spiritual movements.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] It also involved political activities that included the Roman Inquisition.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] New religious orders were a fundamental part of this trend.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Orders such as the Capuchins, Ursulines, Theatines, Discalced Carmelites, the Barnabites, and especially the Jesuits strengthened rural parishes, improved popular piety, helped to curb corruption within the church, and set examples that would be a strong impetus for Catholic renewal.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The Great Divergence in scientific discovery, technological innovation, and economic development began in the early modern period as the pace of change in Western countries increased significantly compared to the rest of the world.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] During the Scientific Revolution of the 16th and 17th centuries, empiricism and modern science replaced older methods of studying nature, which had relied on ancient texts by writers like Aristotle.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] By the time of the Revolution, these methods resulted in an accumulation of knowledge that overturned ideas inherited from ancient Greece and Islamic scholars.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Inventions of the early modern period included the floating dock, lifting tower, newspaper, grenade musket, lightning rod, bifocals, and Franklin stove.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Early attempts at building a practical electrical telegraph were hindered because static electricity was the only source available.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The Age of Enlightenment is also called the Age of Reason because it marked a departure from the medieval tradition of scholasticism, which was rooted in Christian dogma, and from Renaissance philosophy's occultist approaches.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Instead, reason became the central source of knowledge, initiating the era of modern philosophy, especially in Western philosophy.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] This period in Europe was characterized by system-builders—philosophers who established unified theories of epistemology, metaphysics, logic, ethics, and sometimes even politics and the physical sciences.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Early 17th-century philosophy is often referred to as the Age of Rationalism, succeeding Renaissance philosophy and preceding the Enlightenment.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Some consider it the earliest part of the Enlightenment, stretching over two centuries.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] This era includes the works of Isaac Newton (1643–1727), such as Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica (1687), and the development of Descartes' famous proposition Cogito, ergo sum (1637).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The first major advancements in modern science included Newton's theory of gravity, which, along with the contributions of John Locke, Pierre Bayle, Baruch Spinoza, and others, fueled the Enlightenment.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The 18th century saw the rise of secularization in Europe, notably following the French Revolution.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Immanuel Kant classified his predecessors into two philosophical schools: Rationalism and Empiricism.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The former was represented by figures such as René Descartes, Baruch Spinoza, and Gottfried Leibniz.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Roger Williams established the colony of Providence Plantations in New England on the principle of separation of church and state after being exiled by the Puritans of the Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] French salon culture played a key role in spreading Enlightenment ideas, culminating in the influential Encyclopédie (1751–72), edited by Denis Diderot with contributions from thinkers such as Voltaire and Montesquieu.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The Quarrel of the Ancients and the Moderns stirred debate within the French Academy, elevating contemporary knowledge over classical Greek and Roman wisdom.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Enlightenment thought also significantly influenced German philosophy, fostered by Frederick the Great, with Immanuel Kant emerging as a leading figure.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] These developments also had profound impacts on the Scottish Enlightenment, Russian Enlightenment, Enlightenment in Spain, and Enlightenment in Poland.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The Enlightenment flourished until around 1790–1800, after which the emphasis on reason gave way to Romanticism and the growing influence of Counter-Enlightenment movements.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] With the adoption of large-scale printing after 1500, Italian Renaissance Humanism spread northward to France, Germany, Holland and England, where it became associated with the Reformation.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Developing during the Enlightenment era, Renaissance humanism as an intellectual movement spread across Europe.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The basic training of the humanist was to speak well and write (typically, in the form of a letter).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The term *umanista* comes from the latter part of the 15th century.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The people were associated with the *studia humanitatis*, a novel curriculum that was competing with the *quadrivium* and scholastic logic.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] In France, pre-eminent Humanist Guillaume Budé (1467–1540) applied the philological methods of Italian Humanism to the study of antique coinage and to legal history, composing a detailed commentary on Justinian's Code.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Although a royal absolutist (and not a republican like the early Italian *umanisti*), Budé was active in civic life, serving as a diplomat for Francis I and helping to found the Collège des Lecteurs Royaux (later the Collège de France).
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Meanwhile, Marguerite de Navarre, the sister of Francis I, herself a poet, novelist and religious mystic, gathered around her and protected a circle of vernacular poets and writers, including Clément Marot, Pierre de Ronsard and François Rabelais.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] During the early modern period, thorough and accurate global data on mortality rates is limited for a number of reasons including disparities in medical practices and views on the dead.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] However, there still remains data from European countries that still holds valuable information on the mortality rates of infants during this era.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] In his book *Life Under Pressure: Mortality and Living Standards in Europe and Asia, 1700–1900*, Tommy Bengtsson provides adequate information pertaining to the data of infant mortality rates in European countries as well as provide necessary contextual influences on these mortality rates.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Infant mortality was a global concern during the early modern period as many newborns would not survive into childhood.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Bengsston provides comparative data on infant mortality averages in a variety of European towns, cities, regions and countries starting from the mid-1600s to the 1800s.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] These statistics are measured for infant deaths within the first month of every 1,000 births in a given area.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] For instance, the average infant mortality rate in what is now Germany was 108 infant deaths for every 1,000 births; in Bavaria, there were 140–190 infant deaths reported for every 1,000 births.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] In France, Beauvaisis reported 140–160 infants dying per every 1,000 babies born.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] In what is now Italy, Venice averaged 134 infant deaths per 1,000 births.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] In Geneva, 80–110 infants died per every 1,000 babies born.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] In Sweden, 70–95 infants died per 1,000 births in Linköping, 48 infants died per 1,000 births in Sundsvall, and 41 infants died per 1,000 births in Vastanfors.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Bengsston writes that climate conditions were the most important factor in determining infant mortality rates: "For the period from birth to the fifth birthday, [climate] is clearly the most important determinant of death".
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Winters proved to be harsh on families and their newborns, especially if the other seasons of the year were warmer.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] This seasonal drop in temperature was a lot for an infant's body to adapt to.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] For instance, Italy is home to a very warm climate in the summer, and the temperature drops immensely in the winter.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] This lends context to Bengsston writing that "the [Italian] winter peak was the cruelest: during the first 10 days of life, a newborn was four times more likely to die than in the summer".
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] According to Bengsston, this trend existed amongst cities in different parts of Italy and in various parts of Europe even though cities operated under different economic and agricultural conditions.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] This last hypothesis could explain why the effect was so strong in Italy".
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] During the early modern period, many societies' views on death changed greatly.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] With the implementation of new torture techniques, and increased public executions, people began to give more value to their life, and their body after death.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] Along with the views on death, methods of execution also changed.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] New devices to torture and execute criminals were invented.
[src:early-modern-period/early-modern-period-p02] The number of criminals executed by gibbeting increased, as did the total rate of executions during the early modern period.
